{"type":"message","id":"eea7c42c","parentId":"a4ab2902","timestamp":"2026-03-23T15:25:24.409Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Wait, the issue was that the API was rejecting with \"Syntax error\" due to invalid chars. The `-Compress` flag might not be the issue. Let me also check if the prompt with em-dashes was being passed directly in the JSON body without proper escaping.\n\nActually, the real fix is the `Normalize-Text` function that replaces em-dashes and smart quotes. The UTF-8 encoding fix with `[System.Text.Encoding]::UTF8.GetBytes()` is the right approach for ensuring the JSON is properly encoded.\n\nBut wait - `Invoke-RestMethod` in PowerShell Core should handle UTF-8 strings correctly. The issue was the `ConvertTo-Json -Compress` was probably fine, but the em-dash character was causing issues when the server was parsing it.\n \nSo the em-dash U+2014 was getting corrupted during transmission, likely through double-encoding. The `Normalize-Text` function replacing it with a regular hyphen should prevent that, and using `[System.Text.Encoding]::UTF8.GetBytes()` for the request body is the proper way to ensure UTF-8 encoding in PowerShell.\n\nActually, I think the simpler approach is better—just using `ConvertTo-Json` to serialize the body and let PowerShell handle the encoding through the `-Body` parameter, rather than manually converting to bytes. The real issue might be something specific to how the MiniMax API handles the request, so I should verify the API is even responding correctly first.","thinkingSignature":"db09127f9769009e4225b8428b10ece3eda713471529a0b1ecd844dd91a5dc12"},{"type":"text","text":"Now let me test the fix works — run a pulse and check if mutations generate:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_vgfe4yf84awm_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cd C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox; git add -A; git commit -m \"fix: normalize unicode chars in LLM prompt to prevent API syntax errors\" 2>