{"type":"message","id":"82b670c0","parentId":"cea91892","timestamp":"2026-03-23T15:27:37.910Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK, so the M2.7 IS working! It's just returning the response text as content. But the content is the entire conversation turn including the `<think>` token. That seems odd.\n\nWait - looking at the output more carefully, the content is the full `</think>...Hi there!` with the thinking tags included. The model is returning its reasoning. And it's returning content with `finish=stop`.\n\nSo the issue with the sandbox's pulse.ps1 is that when I look at the API call, it passes `$body | ConvertTo-Json -Depth 5 -Compress` through `[System.Text.Encoding]::UTF8.GetBytes()`. But this should work the same as the debug script.\n \nNow I'm comparing my debug script directly against what pulse.ps1 does. The structure looks identical - same endpoint, same headers, same body format with UTF-8 encoding. So why is the debug script getting the full response with `finish=stop` while pulse.ps1 was getting empty content before my fix?\n\nActually, looking back at the very first successful API call I made, I got back an empty message object with `finish_reason=length`. But then when I ran it again later with `max_tokens=500`, I got actual content. The difference seems to be in how the body is being serialized or passed to the API - my manual call had the JSON body passed directly, while the PowerShell script is converting to bytes first. Maybe the encoding or compression is corrupting something.\n\nWait, but the sandbox has been generating empty completions for quite some time based on the pulse logs showing no mutations. Yet when I tested it just now, I got content. So either something changed in my fix, or the issue was intermittent. Let me trace back through what actually happened - I ran a test script earlier and it returned the expected output, so maybe the issue was with how the body was being formatted in that specific test.\n\nLooking at the timing more carefully, the pulse ran at 11:25:30 AM and my test ran after at 11:43 AM, so the API might have just been down or behaving strangely initially. But even when I run the exact same call with the same model and parameters now, it still returns empty - yet the debug script works fine. I'm trying to figure out what the actual difference is between these two approaches. So I ran the same API call twice with identical parameters and got different results—first an empty response with `finish_reason=length`, then a normal response with content. This suggests the model might be hitting some kind of state issue or rate limiting, where the first call with higher token limits triggers a content filter that the second call with lower limits doesn't. Let me test whether reducing `max_tokens` to something smaller like 50 actually makes a difference on the first attempt.\n\nThe `finish_reason=length` indicates the response was truncated because it hit the token limit, but the content itself shouldn't be empty—that's the real problem. Since the debug script is now returning content successfully, the issue might be resolved. I'm wondering if the sandbox's LLM key differs from what I'm using in my tests, which could explain the discrepancy. Looking at the actual execution, the `$apiKey` variable should be set from the `.llm_key` file, and since `git pull` runs at the start of the script, it would have pulled the latest version with the correct key before execution. I'm tracing through the execution flow: git pull happens, then files are read, then the LLM call is made and its response logged, and finally there's another git commit. So the second commit at 11:25:30 captured the pulse log from that execution, but the log file itself was created during the first pulse run at 11:18:47 before my fix was applied.\n\nLet me just run the pulse manually and check if the mutations directory gets populated with content.","thinkingSignature":"e0558d248100046b5817eccf7f4bb03fb93841d8c9d00c4d0d97316df9836896"},{"type":"text","text":"The model IS working — it's returning content. The issue must have been intermittent. Let me now run the pulse directly and check if mutations generate:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_73vaoqh1x6wq_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cd C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox; powershell -File pulse.ps1 2>&1","yieldMs":85000,"timeout":90}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":95253,"output":896,"cacheRead":13714,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":109863,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774279632946}}
