[7m[0m# Update pulse history[0m\r\n[7m[0m$pulseLog = \"$SandboxRoot\\state\\autonomous_pulse.md\"[0m\r\n[7m[0m$entry [0m[7m [0m[7m [0m[7m [0m[7m[0m= [0m[7m[0m\"- [0m[7m[0m$timestamp`: [0m[7m[0m$observation$(if($appliedMutations.Count [0m[7m[0m-gt [0m[7m[0m0) [0m[7m[0m{ [0m[7m[0m\" [0m[7m[0m[applied: [0m[7m[0m$($appliedMutations [0m[7m[0m-join [0m[7m[0m', [0m\r\n[7m[0m')]\" [0m[7m[0m})\"[0m\r\n[7m[0m$existing = if (Test-Path $pulseLog) { Get-Content $pulseLog -Raw } else { \"\" }[0m\r\n[7m[0m$updated  = $existing -replace '(## Pulse History)', \"`$1`n$entry\"[0m\r\n[7m[0m$updated  | Out-File -FilePath $pulseLog -Encoding UTF8[0m\r\n[7m[0m\r\n[7m[0m# Git commit[0m\r\n[7m[0mgit add -A 2>$null[0m\r\n[7m[0mgit commit -m \"pulse: $timestamp\" 2>$null[0m\r\n[7m[0m\r\n[7m[0mWrite-Host \"[sandbox pulse] $timestamp - $observation\"[0m","cwd":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774279681996}}
{"type":"message","id":"9b5c6d13","parentId":"6f5fcc12","timestamp":"2026-03-23T15:28:31.286Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK, the file on disk has `Normalize-Text` in it - confirmed. So the file on disk IS the new version.\n\nBut the log file contains the OLD script content. This is bizarre. The log file is written DURING the execution of the script. So if the script is writing the new version to disk, why would the log contain the old version?\n\nWait - maybe the issue is that the log file is writing `$llmResponse` which is empty, but the log also shows the `$llmPrompt` content (which is the template). But the `$llmPrompt` in the log is the HERE-string content which includes `$(Normalize-Text $goals)`. \n\nThe variable substitutions happen when the script runs, so the HERE-string would expand `$goals` at runtime. But if `$goals` itself has encoding issues from the file, the Normalize-Text function should be handling that. Looking at the escape sequences in the log output - `[7m` and `[0m` are ANSI color codes, which means the terminal is rendering colored text even though the file itself is UTF-8 encoded. The file content shows the HERE-string template with the `$(Normalize-Text $goals)` expression, so the script is definitely executing the new version, but something's causing the old content to appear in the log.\n\nIf the log file contains the old script, that means the script that wrote the log must have been the old version. But the file on disk is the new version, so either the file was swapped out from under the running script, or the execution picked up a cached version instead.\n\nActually, PowerShell doesn't cache script files - it reads the file at runtime. But what if there's a race condition with git? The `git pull` at the start of pulse.ps1 would overwrite local changes if there are remote updates. So the sequence could be: the old script runs and writes its log with old content, then git pull brings down the new version, and then I read the file and see the new content. That would explain the discrepancy I'm seeing.\n\nLet me test this theory by just running the pulse again without git pull and see what actually happens.\n\nActually, the real problem is that the LLM is returning empty responses. Let me trace through what `$llmResponse` actually contains by running the pulse script directly and checking the output - the debug shows the LLM call succeeded, but I need to see what content it's actually returning.\n\nLooking at the script flow, I think I see the issue now: the code block that sets `$resp` using `[System.Text.Encoding]::UTF8.GetBytes()` is incomplete, and then there's a duplicate `Invoke-RestMethod` call with the body passed as a hashtable instead of bytes. This means the second call might be overwriting the first one, or the response isn't being captured properly.\n\nBut actually, the real problem is probably the old Unicode corruption bug - even if it's fixed now, the LLM might have been returning empty content before because of that encoding issue. Let me just manually propose a mutation and apply it to verify the whole cycle works. Looking at the pending actions, there are several concrete tasks to tackle: writing a PowerShell wrapper for the FocusDecayMemory CLI, defining significance scoring for pulse content, tuning the λ parameter empirically, connecting Breakaway pulses to the TemporalAttention backend, and measuring compression ratio. I should pick whichever one makes the most sense to work on next.\n\nActually, Zach said to apply the mutations from the sandbox - and looking at the sandbox state, the mutations directory is empty and the LLM isn't generating new ones. So I need to generate and apply mutations manually. The pending items are clear enough to work with. But first, let me figure out why the LLM is returning empty responses when the debug script shows it should be working.\n\nWait, I'm realizing the debug script ran after my Unicode fix