{"type":"message","id":"2d5e5d2d","parentId":"e03473ec","timestamp":"2026-03-23T15:56:49.566Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_2bsk5r1hdvl8_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"<think>\r\nLet me analyze the current state and determine what concrete action to take.\r\n\r\nLooking at the goals:\r\n- Phase 0 COMPLETE: Sandbox foundation established\r\n- Phase 1 COMPLETE: Architecture cross-analysis + integration spec synthesized\r\n- Several things completed this session including architecture comparison, gap-decay synthesis, and LLM-augmented pulse\r\n\r\nPending items include:\r\n- Write PowerShell wrapper for FocusDecayMemory CLI\r\n- Define `significance` scoring for pulse content\r\n- Tune ? empirically (start: ?=0.7)\r\n- Wire Breakaway pulses to real TemporalAttention backend\r\n- Measure compression ratio\r\n\r\nThere's also a new Phase 1 Advancement about COMPRESSION-CAUSAL DUALITY with a hypothesis that causal structure IS invariant structure.\r\n\r\nGiven the insights and the new hypothesis about Temporal Invariance Compression (TIC), I should take an action that advances this. The next experiment is to test TIC on the last 20 pulse logs, with success criteria of >70% invariant/variant classification.\r\n\r\nA concrete action would be to:\r\n1. Create the COMPRESSION-CAUSAL-DUALITY.md document\r\n2. Start working on the TIC experiment approach\r\n3. Look at the pulse logs to understand what data we have\r\n\r\nLet me look at what files exist. The last pulse was `pulse_2026-03-23 115528.md`. Let me check if there's a logs directory with pulse history.\r\n\r\nGiven the constraints - I need to take ONE concrete action that advances goals, be specific, prefer file edits.\r\n\r\nThe most impactful next step based on the COMPRESSION-CAUSAL DUALITY insight would be to:\r\n1. Document the new insight in the research folder\r\n2. Create an experiment plan for TIC\r\n\r\nLet me create `research/COMPRESSION-CAUSAL-DUALITY.md` with the insight, hypothesis, and experiment plan for TIC. This would be a new file creation that advances the Phase 1 advancement mentioned.\r\n</think>\r\n\r\n### OBSERVATION\r\nThe COMPRESSION-CAUSAL DUALITY insight (causal structure = invariant structure) represents a significant theoretical convergence. The next concrete step is to formalize this in a research document and outline the TIC experiment on pulse logs.\r\n\r\n### ACTION\r\nCreate the research document formalizing the compression-causal duality hypothesis and the Temporal Invariance Compression (TIC) experiment design with success criteria.\r\n\r\n### MUTATION\r\n`\r\nold_text: (new file)\r\nnew_text: # COMPRESSION-CAUSAL DUALITY\r\n**Created:** 2026-03-23\r\n**Status:** Hypothesis Formed\r\n\r\n## Core Insight\r\nProblem 1 (Compression) and Problem 2 (Causal Discovery) are **the SAME problem**.\r\n\r\n## Hypothesis\r\n> **Causal structure IS invariant structure** - A compressor that discovers invariants has necessarily discovered causal relationships.\r\n\r\n## Theoretical Foundation\r\n- Compression seeks patterns that allow prediction with fewer bits\r\n- Causality identifies relationships where A reliably produces B\r\n- **Invariant relationships** = patterns that persist across context changes\r\n- A compressor finding invariants across temporal boundaries HAS discovered causation\r\n\r\n## Implications\r\n| Traditional View | Breakaway Synthesis |\r\n|------------------|---------------------|\r\n| Compression = data reduction | Compression = causal structure extraction |\r\n| Causality = counterfactual reasoning | Causality = invariance detection |\r\n| Phase 1 and Phase 2 separate | Phase 1/2 collapse into unified problem |\r\n\r\n## Temporal Invariance Compression (TIC) Experiment\r\n\r\n### Methodology\r\n1. Collect last 20 pulse logs\r\n2. Identify invariant structures (persist across sessions)\r\n3. Identify variant structures (session-specific decay)\r\n4. Test: Does invariant detection predict next-pulse content?\r\n\r\n### Success Criteria\r\n- **Classification:** >70% invariant/variant classification accuracy\r\n- **Prediction:** >60% next-pulse content prediction from invariants\r\n\r\n### Expected Outcome\r\nIf hypothesis holds: compressible invariants = discovered causal structure\r\nIf hypothesis fails: compression/causality remain decoupled problems\r\n\r\n## Next Steps\r\n- [ ] Build pulse log collector\r\n- [ ] Implement invariant/variant classifier\r\n- [ ] Run TIC on pulse_*.md files\r\n- [ ] Measure compression ratio vs prediction accuracy\r\n`\r\nfile: research/COMPRESSION-CAUSAL-DUALITY.md\r\n`"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":1039,"aggregated":"<think>\r\nLet me analyze the current state and determine what concrete action to take.\r\n\r\nLooking at the goals:\r\n- Phase 0 COMPLETE: Sandbox foundation established\r\n- Phase 1 COMPLETE: Architecture cross-analysis + integration spec synthesized\r\n- Several things completed this session including architecture comparison, gap-decay synthesis, and LLM-augmented pulse\r\n\r\nPending items include:\r\n- Write PowerShell wrapper for FocusDecayMemory CLI\r\n- Define `significance` scoring for pulse content\r\n- Tune ? empirically (start: ?=0.7)\r\n- Wire Breakaway pulses to real TemporalAttention backend\r\n- Measure compression ratio\r\n\r\nThere's also a new Phase 1 Advancement about COMPRESSION-CAUSAL DUALITY with a hypothesis that causal structure IS invariant structure.\r\n\r\nGiven the insights and the new hypothesis about Temporal Invariance Compression (TIC), I should take an action that advances this. The next experiment is to test TIC on the last 20 pulse logs, with success criteria of >70% invariant/variant classification.\r\n\r\nA concrete action would be to:\r\n1. Create the COMPRESSION-CAUSAL-DUALITY.md document\r\n2. Start working on the TIC experiment approach\r\n3. Look at the pulse logs to understand what data we have\r\n\r\nLet me look at what files exist. The last pulse was `pulse_2026-03-23 115528.md`. Let me check if there's a logs directory with pulse history.\r\n\r\nGiven the constraints - I need to take ONE concrete action that advances goals, be specific, prefer file edits.\r\n\r\nThe most impactful next step based on the COMPRESSION-CAUSAL DUALITY insight would be to:\r\n1. Document the new insight in the research folder\r\n2. Create an experiment plan for TIC\r\n\r\nLet me create `research/COMPRESSION-CAUSAL-DUALITY.md` with the insight, hypothesis, and experiment plan for TIC. This would be a new file creation that advances the Phase 1 advancement mentioned.\r\n</think>\r\n\r\n### OBSERVATION\r\nThe COMPRESSION-CAUSAL DUALITY insight (causal structure = invariant structure) represents a significant theoretical convergence. The next concrete step is to formalize this in a research document and outline the TIC experiment on pulse logs.\r\n\r\n### ACTION\r\nCreate the research document formalizing the compression-causal duality hypothesis and the Temporal Invariance Compression (TIC) experiment design with success criteria.\r\n\r\n### MUTATION\r\n`\r\nold_text: (new file)\r\nnew_text: # COMPRESSION-CAUSAL DUALITY\r\n**Created:** 2026-03-23\r\n**Status:** Hypothesis Formed\r\n\r\n## Core Insight\r\nProblem 1 (Compression) and Problem 2 (Causal Discovery) are **the SAME problem**.\r\n\r\n## Hypothesis\r\n> **Causal structure IS invariant structure** - A compressor that discovers invariants has necessarily discovered causal relationships.\r\n\r\n## Theoretical Foundation\r\n- Compression seeks patterns that allow prediction with fewer bits\r\n- Causality identifies relationships where A reliably produces B\r\n- **Invariant relationships** = patterns that persist across context changes\r\n- A compressor finding invariants across temporal boundaries HAS discovered causation\r\n\r\n## Implications\r\n| Traditional View | Breakaway Synthesis |\r\n|------------------|---------------------|\r\n| Compression = data reduction | Compression = causal structure extraction |\r\n| Causality = counterfactual reasoning | Causality = invariance detection |\r\n| Phase 1 and Phase 2 separate | Phase 1/2 collapse into unified problem |\r\n\r\n## Temporal Invariance Compression (TIC) Experiment\r\n\r\n### Methodology\r\n1. Collect last 20 pulse logs\r\n2. Identify invariant structures (persist across sessions)\r\n3. Identify variant structures (session-specific decay)\r\n4. Test: Does invariant detection predict next-pulse content?\r\n\r\n### Success Criteria\r\n- **Classification:** >70% invariant/variant classification accuracy\r\n- **Prediction:** >60% next-pulse content prediction from invariants\r\n\r\n### Expected Outcome\r\nIf hypothesis holds: compressible invariants = discovered causal structure\r\nIf hypothesis fails: compression/causality remain decoupled problems\r\n\r\n## Next Steps\r\n- [ ] Build pulse log collector\r\n- [ ] Implement invariant/variant classifier\r\n- [ ] Run TIC on pulse_*.md files\r\n- [ ] Measure compression ratio vs prediction accuracy\r\n`\r\nfile: research/COMPRESSION-CAUSAL-DUALITY.md\r\n`","cwd":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774281409543}}
{"type":"message","id":"7957cfb2","parentId":"2d5e5d2d","timestamp":"2026-03-23T15:57:14.682Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The mutation was proposed! The `old_text: (new file)` was found and the new file was created. But the mutation parser said \"new_text_len=0\" and \"mutation parse failed\". This means the mutation WAS written to the proposed directory but with empty new_text. Let me check.Actually, looking at the pulse output: \"[mutation parse failed] old_text=(new file) file=research/COMPRESSION-CAUSAL-DUALITY.md new_text_len=0\". So the mutation was proposed BUT with old_text=(new file) and new_text=0. The file field was set correctly.The issue is that the mutation format uses `(new file)` as old_text and the content as new_text. \n\nSo the parser extracted the file path correctly but couldn't pull the new_text content from between the markers. I need to trace through how the new_text extraction works - it looks for content between \"new_text:\" and \"file:\" using regex, but something's going wrong there. The parser found the right file path from the end of the block, but the new_text content itself is coming back empty, which means the regex pattern for capturing that section isn't matching the actual format in the response.\n\nLooking at the regex more carefully, it's trying to match the new_text section with `(?s)new_text:\\s*\\n(.+?)\\s*\\n\\s*file:` using Singleline mode, which should capture everything between new_text: and file: as long as there's a newline after new_text: and file: appears at the end. The regex should theoretically work, but maybe the actual text doesn't match this exact pattern - perhaps the whitespace or newlines aren't quite what the regex expects.\n\nSince the pulse output shows \"mutation parse failed\" but also shows \"old_text=(new file) file=research/COMPRESSION-CAUSAL-DUALITY.md new_text_len=0\", I can tell the parser at least found the file line correctly. The real problem is new_text_len is 0, meaning the regex for capturing new_text content isn't matching anything.\n\nLooking at what actually got written to the .mutation file - it seems like only the first line of the MUTATION block ended up in the file. The opening line `old_text: (new file)` was captured, but the actual content from the MUTATION block itself wasn't included, which suggests the regex is only grabbing the first line before hitting the triple backticks and stopping. I'm realizing the mutation file format might be structured as file path on the first line, then `---`, then the old text or `[NEW_FILE]`, then `---`, then the new text content. If the LLM response contained something like `old_text: (new file)` at the start of a MUTATION block, the parser might have grabbed that literally instead of recognizing `(new file)` as a special marker, which would explain why the actual content never made it into the mutation file. I see the issue now—the parser is extracting `old_text: (new file)` from inside the MUTATION block rather than recognizing it as the special marker for new files. The regex pattern `'old_text:\\s*(.+)'` is capturing everything after \"old_text:\" including the parentheses, so it's treating `(new file)` as literal text instead of the special indicator that means \"create a new file\".\n\nThe core problem is that the parser needs to distinguish between `old_text: (new file)` which means \"create new file\" versus `old_text: some actual text here` which means \"replace this existing text\". When the LLM writes the MUTATION block with `old_text: (new file)`, the parser should recognize this as the new file indicator and set the old_text to `[NEW_FILE]`, but instead it's preserving the literal `(new file)` string.\n\nThe fix is to check if the extracted oldLine equals \"(new file)\" and if so, treat it as a new file creation rather than an edit operation. This way the mutation file format correctly distinguishes between creating a new file versus modifying an existing one, and the reconstruction logic can handle both cases appropriately.\n\nNow I should verify whether this bug actually caused a mutation to be proposed—let me check the proposed directory.","thinkingSignature":"74e3d645eca32d9139b31ca6bc6100a2edc374549899386096d24944d5e577eb"},{"type":"text","text":"The mutation was found! But the parser bug: it extracted `(new file)` literally instead of treating it as a file-creation signal. Let me check if it was saved, then fix the parser:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_57gr4j9rjmzs_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"Get-ChildItem \"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\mutations\\proposed\" -File 2>$null | Select-Object Name, Length, LastWriteTime","timeout":5}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":91455,"output":979,"cacheRead":13731,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":106165,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774281409572}}
