{"type":"message","id":"7c0b24a6","parentId":"cbe70f8a","timestamp":"2026-03-23T15:58:33.608Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_ia3u4fk334m9_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Directory: C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\mutations\\proposed\r\n\r\n[32;1mMode   [0m[32;1m              LastWriteTime[0m[32;1m         Length[0m[32;1m Name[0m\r\n[32;1m----   [0m [32;1m             -------------[0m [32;1m        ------[0m [32;1m----[0m\r\n-a---           3/23/2026 11:57 AM             40 2026-03-23 115728.mutation"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":1120,"aggregated":"Directory: C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\mutations\\proposed\r\n\r\n[32;1mMode   [0m[32;1m              LastWriteTime[0m[32;1m         Length[0m[32;1m Name[0m\r\n[32;1m----   [0m [32;1m             -------------[0m [32;1m        ------[0m [32;1m----[0m\r\n-a---           3/23/2026 11:57 AM             40 2026-03-23 115728.mutation","cwd":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774281513578}}
{"type":"message","id":"7811cb2d","parentId":"7c0b24a6","timestamp":"2026-03-23T15:59:07.871Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Only one mutation file exists and it's the old broken one. The new mutation was proposed (we saw \"[mutation proposed]\" in the output) but the file is still the old one. Wait - the timestamp of the mutation file is 11:57 AM, which is from the earlier pulse. The second mutation proposal must have failed to write because the file was already locked or something.\n\nActually, looking at the pulse output again:\n```\n[mutation proposed] \", \"old_text:\")\n```\nThis says the mutation was proposed. But the file content shows the old (wrong) content. And the file timestamp is 11:57 AM which was from the FIRST successful proposal. The second proposal didn't overwrite the file because... maybe the file write failed silently?\n\n\nSo the second pulse ran and created a new log file, but the mutation proposal hit a snag - the mutation file still contains that malformed content `\", \"old_text:\")`. I need to figure out what the parser is actually capturing from the MUTATION block. Looking at the regex pattern being used, it's trying to extract content between the triple backticks, but something's going wrong with how it's parsing the boundaries or capturing the actual content. I'm realizing the regex might be matching too broadly - if the LLM response contains something like `{\"field\": \"old_text: value\", ...}` wrapped in triple backticks, the pattern `(?s)new_text:\\s*\\n(.+?)\\s*\\n\\s*file:` could match across those boundaries incorrectly, capturing `{\"field\": \"old_text\": \"` as the content instead of stopping at the actual delimiter.\n\nThe core issue seems to be that the MUTATION block structure itself is ambiguous - the opening ``` might not be on its own line as expected, which throws off where the block actually starts and ends. I'm realizing the regex for the new_text field is capturing content that extends all the way to the last occurrence of \"file:\" in the block, which means it's pulling in unintended content from the surrounding JSON structure rather than stopping at the actual file field within the MUTATION block itself.\n\nLooking at what actually got extracted, the file field ended up with the malformed value `\", \"old_text:\")` instead of a proper path, which suggests the greedy matching is consuming content from the wrong section of the JSON and then the file regex is picking up something from that contaminated text.\n\nThe real issue is that the MUTATION block itself isn't properly delimited—the opening ``` is part of the JSON response wrapper, not a true line boundary for the block, so when I search for \"file:\" I'm finding it inside the JSON structure rather than in the actual MUTATION block where it should be.\n\nI think the fix is to use a negative lookahead to ensure \"file:\" isn't followed by another colon (which would indicate it's inside a JSON value like `\"file:\"`), and to anchor the search to lines that actually start with \"file:\" rather than searching anywhere in the text. I'm overcomplicating the regex approach here. The real issue is that the parser is matching the JSON wrapper's backticks instead of the MUTATION block's actual delimiters. A simpler fix would be to have the LLM format the MUTATION block differently—perhaps using a structure that clearly separates the file path from other fields, like putting `file:` on its own line or using a delimiter that's unlikely to appear in the content itself.\n\nBut actually, I think the cleanest solution is to be more specific about where the MUTATION block starts. I can find the `### MUTATION` header and only search within that section, rather than relying on the triple backticks as boundaries. That way the parser won't accidentally pick up markers from the JSON wrapper.\n\nLet me also make the regex patterns themselves more robust by anchoring them to line starts and being explicit about what characters can follow.","thinkingSignature":"dbb295ef620c3634f68d33a692c9ea061fcd58e1f9547bfd3e7621a657d8292a"},{"type":"text","text":"The parser is matching `file:` inside JSON fields of the LLM response instead of the MUTATION block. Let me fix the regex to be more precise:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_x6kuh9vdh1tw_1","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\pulse.ps1","oldText":"# Parse MUTATION block — extract old_text, new_text (multiline), and file from the block\n$mutationProposed = $false\n$mStart = $llmResponse.IndexOf('### MUTATION')\nif ($mStart -ge 0) {\n    $block = $llmResponse.Substring($mStart)\n    # Remove ALL code fences (replace each fence pair with placeholder, repeat until stable)\n    $prev = \"\"\n    while ($prev -ne $block) { $prev = $block; $block = $block -replace '(?s)```.*?```', \"`n[CODE_BLOCK]`n\" }\n    # Extract fields\n    $oldMatch = [regex]::Match($block, 'old_text:\\s*(.+)')\n    $fileMatch = [regex]::Match($block, 'file:\\s*(.+)')\n    $oldLine = if ($oldMatch.Success) { $oldMatch.Groups[1].Value.Trim() } else { \"\" }\n    $fileLine = if ($fileMatch.Success) { $fileMatch.Groups[1].Value.Trim() } else { \"\" }\n    # new_text: between \"new_text:\" line and \"file:\" line (after fence removal)\n    $newText = \"\"\n    if ($oldLine -and $fileLine) {\n        $ntMatch = [regex]::Match($block, '(?s)new_text:\\s*\\n(.+?)\\s*\\n\\s*file:', [System.Text.RegularExpressions.RegexOptions]::Singleline)\n        if ($ntMatch.Success) { $newText = $ntMatch.Groups[1].Value.Trim() }\n    }\n    # Fallback: if file missing, try to extract from ACTION block\n    if (-not $fileLine) {\n        $actionMatch = [regex]::Match($llmResponse, '(?s)### ACTION\\s*\\n(.+?)(?:\\n###|$)')\n        if ($actionMatch.Success) {\n            $actionText = $actionMatch.Groups[1].Value\n            # Match \"Create `path/file.md`\" or \"Edit `path/file.md`\" with or without backticks\n            $fileInference = [regex]::Match($actionText, '(?:Create|Edit|Update|New file)[:\\s]+(?:``([^``]+)``|([^\\s]+))')\n            if ($fileInference.Success) {\n                $fileLine = if ($fileInference.Groups[2].Value) { $fileInference.Groups[2].Value } else { $fileInference.Groups[1].Value }\n                Write-Host \"[file inferred from ACTION] $fileLine\"\n            }\n        }\n    }\n    if ($oldLine -and $fileLine) {\n        $isNewFile = ($oldLine.Trim() -eq \"(new file)\")\n        $mutationContent = \"$fileLine`n---`n$(if($isNewFile) { '[NEW_FILE]' } else { $oldLine })`n---`n$newText\"","new_string":"# Parse MUTATION block — extract old_text, new_text (multiline), and file from the block\n# Key fix: search ONLY within the MUTATION block, and use line-anchored patterns\n$mutationProposed = $false\n$mStart = $llmResponse.IndexOf('### MUTATION')\nif ($mStart -ge 0) {\n    $block = $llmResponse.Substring($mStart)\n    # Remove ALL code fences first\n    $prev = \"\"\n    while ($prev -ne $block) { $prev = $block; $block = $block -replace '(?s)```.*?```', \"`n[CODE_BLOCK]`n\" }\n    # Extract ONLY from the first code block inside MUTATION (the actual content)\n    $codeBlockMatch = [regex]::Match($block, '(?s)```\\s*\\n(.*?)\\n```')\n    if ($codeBlockMatch.Success) {\n        $codeContent = $codeBlockMatch.Groups[1].Value\n        # Parse fields from the code block content (newline-separated key: value)\n        $lines = $codeContent -split \"`n\"\n        $oldLine = \"\"\n        $newText = \"\"\n        $fileLine = \"\"\n        foreach ($line in $lines) {\n            if ($line -match '^old_text:\\s*(.+)') { $oldLine = $Matches[1].Trim() }\n            if ($line -match '^new_text:\\s*(.*)') { $newText = $Matches[1].Trim() }\n            if ($line -match '^file:\\s*(.+)') { $fileLine = $Matches[1].Trim() }\n        }\n    }\n    # Fallback: if file missing, try to extract from ACTION block\n    if (-not $fileLine) {\n        $actionMatch = [regex]::Match($llmResponse, '(?s)### ACTION\\s*\\n(.+?)(?:\\n###|$)')\n        if ($actionMatch.Success) {\n            $actionText = $actionMatch.Groups[1].Value\n            $fileInference = [regex]::Match($actionText, '(?:Create|Edit|Update|New file)[:\\s]+(?:``([^``]+)``|([^\\s]+))')\n            if ($fileInference.Success) {\n                $fileLine = if ($fileInference.Groups[2].Value) { $fileInference.Groups[2].Value } else { $fileInference.Groups[1].Value }\n                Write-Host \"[file inferred from ACTION] $fileLine\"\n            }\n        }\n    }\n    if ($oldLine -and $fileLine) {\n        $isNewFile = ($oldLine.Trim() -eq \"(new file)\")\n        $mutationContent = \"$fileLine`n---`n$(if($isNewFile) { '[NEW_FILE]' } else { $oldLine })`n---`n$newText\""}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":89159,"output":2127,"cacheRead":13731,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":105017,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774281513614}}
