{"type":"message","id":"6d0838be","parentId":"b6a455bb","timestamp":"2026-03-23T16:04:44.822Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Wait, the issue might not be the python path. When I ran the test script earlier (`test_llm_prompt3.ps1`), it had encoding issues with heredoc strings. The sandbox pulse.ps1 doesn't use heredocs for the prompt anymore (we replaced with file-based approach), but the prompt is being written via PowerShell's `Out-File`.\n\nActually, let me think about this differently. The test that worked was:1. `python call_llm.py prompt.txt` - worked, got 3563 chars\n\nThe test that failed was pulse.ps1 calling it via Process::Start. Let me check if there's a working direct test that calls Python from PowerShell via Process::Start.Actually, wait. Looking at the test_mx3.ps1 that worked:\n\n\nI'm running a Python script through PowerShell's Process::Start to test an LLM call. The script takes a prompt from a text file, sends it to an API, and writes the response to a file. It outputs the content length and first 400 characters of the response, and it worked fine. Let me just run the pulse and see if the Python path fix resolves the issue.","thinkingSignature":"53f5ffc5bf8b13ff59afaff6248349aef8f9fd425582f6b40b1cac467eb988d2"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_sd73kfuftije_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cd C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox; powershell -File pulse.ps1 2>&1","yieldMs":85000,"timeout":90}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":98123,"output":309,"cacheRead":13731,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":112163,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774281876897}}
{"type":"message","id":"b51e3f77","parentId":"6d0838be","timestamp":"2026-03-23T16:05:08.481Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_sd73kfuftije_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[LLM] response length: 4924\n[DEBUG] code block not matched. Looking for new_text field directly in block...\n[DEBUG] direct parse: old_line='' file_line='' new_text_len=0\n[file inferred from ACTION] the\n[mutation parse failed] old_text= file=the new_text_len=0\n[master ba6d13c] pulse: 2026-03-23 120445\n 5 files changed, 243 insertions(+), 3 deletions(-)\n create mode 100644 memory/session/pulse_2026-03-23 120445.md\n[sandbox pulse] 2026-03-23 120445 - The COMPRESSION-CAUSAL DUALITY insight provides a concrete unification of Phase 1 and Phase 2, but the TIC (Temporal Invariance Compression) experiment needs a concrete methodology and the significance scoring must be defined before any empirical testing can begin."}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":23584,"aggregated":"[LLM] response length: 4924\n[DEBUG] code block not matched. Looking for new_text field directly in block...\n[DEBUG] direct parse: old_line='' file_line='' new_text_len=0\n[file inferred from ACTION] the\n[mutation parse failed] old_text= file=the new_text_len=0\n[master ba6d13c] pulse: 2026-03-23 120445\n 5 files changed, 243 insertions(+), 3 deletions(-)\n create mode 100644 memory/session/pulse_2026-03-23 120445.md\n[sandbox pulse] 2026-03-23 120445 - The COMPRESSION-CAUSAL DUALITY insight provides a concrete unification of Phase 1 and Phase 2, but the TIC (Temporal Invariance Compression) experiment needs a concrete methodology and the significance scoring must be defined before any empirical testing can begin.","cwd":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774281908429}}
{"type":"message","id":"330b8b1c","parentId":"b51e3f77","timestamp":"2026-03-23T16:05:13.297Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK, 4924 chars back - that's a real response. The mutation parse is still failing though. Let me look at the actual LLM response to understand the format it's using:","thinkingSignature":"800e94e633c5afca98d4eaeda5466da253a95209c88bf5ee5e3fb0c1a109b7ad"},{"type":"text","text":"Good, 4924 chars back. Still failing to parse. Let me see the actual response format:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_cc0hs1ev41nw_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"Get-Content \"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\.llm_response.txt\" -Raw -Encoding UTF8 2>$null | Select-Object -Last 1000","timeout":5}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":98641,"output":132,"cacheRead":13731,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":112504,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774281908486}}
{"type":"message","id":"d85aad69","parentId":"330b8b1c","timestamp":"2026-03-23T16:05:14.413Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_cc0hs1ev41nw_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"<think>\r\nLet me analyze the current state and what action to take.\r\n\r\nCurrent situation:\r\n- Phase 0 and Phase 1 are marked complete\r\n- There's been significant synthesis work done\r\n- Key pending items include:\r\n  - Write PowerShell wrapper for FocusDecayMemory CLI\r\n  - Define `significance` scoring for pulse content\r\n  - Tune ? empirically\r\n  - Wire Breakaway pulses to real TemporalAttention backend\r\n  - Measure compression ratio\r\n\r\nThe latest insight is about \"COMPRESSION-CAUSAL DUALITY\" - the idea that Problem 1 (Compression) and Problem 2 (Causal Discovery) are the same problem. The hypothesis is that causal structure IS invariant structure.\r\n\r\nThe \"Next experiment\" mentioned is Temporal Invariance Compression (TIC) - test on last 20 pulse logs.\r\n\r\nSuccess criteria: >70% invariant/variant classification, >60% next-pulse prediction.\r\n\r\nLooking at what's available in the sandbox, I need to understand what files exist and what concrete action I can take.\r\n\r\nThe most actionable and concrete task would be to:\r\n1. Look at the last 20 pulse logs to understand the data\r\n2. Begin designing the TIC experiment\r\n3. Or create the significance scoring framework\r\n\r\nLet me think about what would be most productive:\r\n\r\n1. The PowerShell wrapper for FocusDecayMemory CLI - needs external tool knowledge\r\n2. Significance scoring - this is a core algorithm piece that could be defined\r\n3. Tuning ? - needs data\r\n4. Wire to TemporalAttention backend - needs external system\r\n5. Measure compression ratio - needs both original and summarized\r\n\r\nGiven the COMPRESSION-CAUSAL DUALITY insight and the TIC experiment that's been proposed, a good concrete action would be to:\r\n- Look at the pulse logs to understand their structure\r\n- Start defining the significance scoring function\r\n- Or create a draft of the TIC experiment methodology\r\n\r\nLet me check what pulse log files exist and create a plan for the TIC experiment or define the significance scoring.\r\n\r\n\r\nI'll focus on creating a concrete implementation strategy for the TIC experiment. The key is to develop a systematic approach that can test the compression-causal duality hypothesis. I'll start by defining a clear methodology for analyzing the pulse logs, creating a structured framework for identifying invariants and variants in the temporal data.\r\n</think>\r\n\r\n### OBSERVATION\r\nThe COMPRESSION-CAUSAL DUALITY insight provides a concrete unification of Phase 1 and Phase 2, but the TIC (Temporal Invariance Compression) experiment needs a concrete methodology and the significance scoring must be defined before any empirical testing can begin.\r\n\r\n### ACTION\r\nCreate the significance scoring framework and TIC experiment methodology based on the compression-causality duality. This defines how to score pulse content for invariant/variant classification, which is prerequisite for all empirical work.\r\n\r\n### MUTATION\r\n```\r\nold_text: (new file)\r\nnew_text: # Temporal Invariance Compression (TIC) - Experiment Design\r\n## Core Hypothesis\r\n> Causal structure IS invariant structure - compressor that finds invariants has discovered causation\r\n\r\n## Significance Scoring Framework\r\n\r\n### Definition\r\n`significance(s, ?)` measures how much content `s` changes the probability distribution of future states.\r\n\r\n```\r\nsignificance(s, ?) = ? x persistence(s) + (1-?) x novelty(s)\r\n```\r\n\r\nWhere:\r\n- `persistence(s)` = P(content survives next K pulses | appears in pulse s)\r\n- `novelty(s)` = -log(P(content | all previous pulses)) - information gain\r\n\r\n### ? Parameter (Tuning)\r\n- ? ? [0, 1] controls decay rate AND gap sensitivity threshold\r\n- Start: ? = 0.7 (per pending actions)\r\n- ? � 1.0: only persistent content matters (slow decay)\r\n- ? � 0.0: only novel content matters (fast decay)\r\n\r\n## TIC Algorithm (Draft)\r\n\r\n```\r\n1. For each pulse p[i] in last N pulses:\r\n   a. Extract content tokens T[i]\r\n   b. For each token t ? T[i]:\r\n      - Compute significance(t, ?)\r\n      - Classify: significance > threshold  INVARIANT\r\n                 significance � threshold  VARIANT\r\n\r\n2. For next-pulse prediction:\r\n   - Given pulse p[i], predict p[i+1] as:\r\n     - Invariant tokens from p[i] (high confidence persistence)\r\n     - Null placeholder for variant tokens (information loss zone)\r\n\r\n3. Evaluate:\r\n   - Classification accuracy: predicted invariant/variant vs actual\r\n   - Prediction accuracy: next-pulse reconstruction vs actual\r\n```\r\n\r\n## Success Criteria\r\n- >70% invariant/variant classification accuracy\r\n- >60% next-pulse prediction accuracy\r\n\r\n## Test Data\r\n- Pulse logs: `logs/pulse_*.md` (last 20)\r\n- Baseline: raw concatenation (no compression)\r\n- Comparison: TemporalAttention focus_decay output\r\n\r\n## Next Steps\r\n1. [ ] Implement significance() in pulse analysis script\r\n2. [ ] Run TIC on last 20 pulse logs\r\n3. [ ] Tune ? empirically (grid search 0.5-0.9)\r\n4. [ ] Compare against TemporalAttention focus_decay baseline\r\nfile: research/TIC-EXPERIMENT.md\r\n```"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":1068,"aggregated":"<think>\r\nLet me analyze the current state and what action to take.\r\n\r\nCurrent situation:\r\n- Phase 0 and Phase 1 are marked complete\r\n- There's been significant synthesis work done\r\n- Key pending items include:\r\n  - Write PowerShell wrapper for FocusDecayMemory CLI\r\n  - Define `significance` scoring for pulse content\r\n  - Tune ? empirically\r\n  - Wire Breakaway pulses to real TemporalAttention backend\r\n  - Measure compression ratio\r\n\r\nThe latest insight is about \"COMPRESSION-CAUSAL DUALITY\" - the idea that Problem 1 (Compression) and Problem 2 (Causal Discovery) are the same problem. The hypothesis is that causal structure IS invariant structure.\r\n\r\nThe \"Next experiment\" mentioned is Temporal Invariance Compression (TIC) - test on last 20 pulse logs.\r\n\r\nSuccess criteria: >70% invariant/variant classification, >60% next-pulse prediction.\r\n\r\nLooking at what's available in the sandbox, I need to understand what files exist and what concrete action I can take.\r\n\r\nThe most actionable and concrete task would be to:\r\n1. Look at the last 20 pulse logs to understand the data\r\n2. Begin designing the TIC experiment\r\n3. Or create the significance scoring framework\r\n\r\nLet me think about what would be most productive:\r\n\r\n1. The PowerShell wrapper for FocusDecayMemory CLI - needs external tool knowledge\r\n2. Significance scoring - this is a core algorithm piece that could be defined\r\n3. Tuning ? - needs data\r\n4. Wire to TemporalAttention backend - needs external system\r\n5. Measure compression ratio - needs both original and summarized\r\n\r\nGiven the COMPRESSION-CAUSAL DUALITY insight and the TIC experiment that's been proposed, a good concrete action would be to:\r\n- Look at the pulse logs to understand their structure\r\n- Start defining the significance scoring function\r\n- Or create a draft of the TIC experiment methodology\r\n\r\nLet me check what pulse log files exist and create a plan for the TIC experiment or define the significance scoring.\r\n\r\n\r\nI'll focus on creating a concrete implementation strategy for the TIC experiment. The key is to develop a systematic approach that can test the compression-causal duality hypothesis. I'll start by defining a clear methodology for analyzing the pulse logs, creating a structured framework for identifying invariants and variants in the temporal data.\r\n</think>\r\n\r\n### OBSERVATION\r\nThe COMPRESSION-CAUSAL DUALITY insight provides a concrete unification of Phase 1 and Phase 2, but the TIC (Temporal Invariance Compression) experiment needs a concrete methodology and the significance scoring must be defined before any empirical testing can begin.\r\n\r\n### ACTION\r\nCreate the significance scoring framework and TIC experiment methodology based on the compression-causality duality. This defines how to score pulse content for invariant/variant classification, which is prerequisite for all empirical work.\r\n\r\n### MUTATION\r\n```\r\nold_text: (new file)\r\nnew_text: # Temporal Invariance Compression (TIC) - Experiment Design\r\n## Core Hypothesis\r\n> Causal structure IS invariant structure - compressor that finds invariants has discovered causation\r\n\r\n## Significance Scoring Framework\r\n\r\n### Definition\r\n`significance(s, ?)` measures how much content `s` changes the probability distribution of future states.\r\n\r\n```\r\nsignificance(s, ?) = ? x persistence(s) + (1-?) x novelty(s)\r\n```\r\n\r\nWhere:\r\n- `persistence(s)` = P(content survives next K pulses | appears in pulse s)\r\n- `novelty(s)` = -log(P(content | all previous pulses)) - information gain\r\n\r\n### ? Parameter (Tuning)\r\n- ? ? [0, 1] controls decay rate AND gap sensitivity threshold\r\n- Start: ? = 0.7 (per pending actions)\r\n- ? � 1.0: only persistent content matters (slow decay)\r\n- ? � 0.0: only novel content matters (fast decay)\r\n\r\n## TIC Algorithm (Draft)\r\n\r\n```\r\n1. For each pulse p[i] in last N pulses:\r\n   a. Extract content tokens T[i]\r\n   b. For each token t ? T[i]:\r\n      - Compute significance(t, ?)\r\n      - Classify: significance > threshold  INVARIANT\r\n                 significance � threshold  VARIANT\r\n\r\n2. For next-pulse prediction:\r\n   - Given pulse p[i], predict p[i+1] as:\r\n     - Invariant tokens from p[i] (high confidence persistence)\r\n     - Null placeholder for variant tokens (information loss zone)\r\n\r\n3. Evaluate:\r\n   - Classification accuracy: predicted invariant/variant vs actual\r\n   - Prediction accuracy: next-pulse reconstruction vs actual\r\n```\r\n\r\n## Success Criteria\r\n- >70% invariant/variant classification accuracy\r\n- >60% next-pulse prediction accuracy\r\n\r\n## Test Data\r\n- Pulse logs: `logs/pulse_*.md` (last 20)\r\n- Baseline: raw concatenation (no compression)\r\n- Comparison: TemporalAttention focus_decay output\r\n\r\n## Next Steps\r\n1. [ ] Implement significance() in pulse analysis script\r\n2. [ ] Run TIC on last 20 pulse logs\r\n3. [ ] Tune ? empirically (grid search 0.5-0.9)\r\n4. [ ] Compare against TemporalAttention focus_decay baseline\r\nfile: research/TIC-EXPERIMENT.md\r\n```","cwd":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774281914390}}
