{"type":"message","id":"878a6f92","parentId":"9080945b","timestamp":"2026-03-23T16:07:15.056Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Wait, the Python regex `(?s)```\\s*\\n(.*?)\\n``` ` won't match because the content has triple backticks embedded within the new_text field (like when the LLM writes markdown code blocks). So the non-greedy `.*?` will stop at the first ` ``` ` it finds inside the content!\n\nFor example, in the content:\n```\n### MUTATION\n```\nold_text: (new file)\nnew_text: # Temporal Invariance Compression (TIC) - Experiment Design\n## Core Hypothesis\n> ...\n```\nsignificance(s, λ) = λ × persistence(s) + (1-λ) × novelty(s)\n\n\n```\n\nThe regex `(?s)```\\s*\\n(.*?)\\n``` ` would match from the opening ``` to the FIRST ``` it finds, which is inside the new_text content (after \"significance(s, λ) = ...\")! That's why it's not working. The fix is to match the outer triple backticks by using a negative lookahead or by matching content that doesn't contain triple backticks.\n\nActually, the real problem is that the LLM output itself contains triple backticks as part of its response content, so I need a regex that can distinguish between the opening/closing backticks of the MUTATION block versus the backticks that are just part of the markdown text. The approach should be to match from `### MUTATION` all the way to the final ` ``` ` that closes the entire block, not just any triple backtick sequence.\n\n```\n### MUTATION\n```\n...all the content including any ``` blocks inside...\n```\n```\n\nLet me refine the pattern to match the complete block from opening to closing triple backticks, accounting for the fact that the LLM might generate ``` inside the content itself. The key is recognizing that after the MUTATION header comes a newline, then triple backticks marking the block start, then all the content, then triple backticks marking the end.","thinkingSignature":"658db0940b052b88909564d5bdfa72a7dc1d25690111441623df2f2992817735"},{"type":"text","text":"\nFound the bug. The regex `(?s)```\\s*\\n(.*?)\\n``` ` matches the FIRST ` ``` ` it finds, but the LLM's markdown content has embedded ` ``` ` blocks. The non-greedy `.*?` stops too early.\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_4jcebew7wan7_1","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\pulse.ps1","oldText":"    # Extract ONLY from the first code block inside MUTATION\n    # Handle BOTH single-backtick (`) and triple-backtick (```) fences\n    $codeBlockMatch = [regex]::Match($block, '(?s)`{3}\\s*\\n(.*?)\\n`{3}')\n    if (-not $codeBlockMatch.Success) {\n        $codeBlockMatch = [regex]::Match($block, '(?s)`\\s*\\n(.*?)\\n`')\n    }\n    if ($codeBlockMatch.Success) {\n        $codeContent = $codeBlockMatch.Groups[1].Value\n        Write-Host \"[DEBUG] codeContent length: $($codeContent.Length)\"\n        # Parse fields from the code block content (newline-separated key: value)\n        $lines = $codeContent -split \"`n\"\n        $oldLine = \"\"\n        $newText = \"\"\n        $fileLine = \"\"\n        foreach ($line in $lines) {\n            if ($line -match '^old_text:\\s*(.+)') { $oldLine = $Matches[1].Trim() }\n            if ($line -match '^new_text:\\s*(.*)') { $newText = $Matches[1].Trim() }\n            if ($line -match '^file:\\s*(.+)') { $fileLine = $Matches[1].Trim() }\n        }\n        Write-Host \"[DEBUG] parsed: old_line='$oldLine' file_line='$fileLine' new_text_len=$($newText.Length)\"\n    } else {\n        Write-Host \"[DEBUG] code block not matched. Looking for new_text field directly in block...\"\n        # Direct search for the field lines (fallback)\n        $oldMatch = [regex]::Match($block, '(?im)^old_text:\\s*(.+)')\n        $newMatch = [regex]::Match($block, '(?im)^new_text:\\s*(.+)')\n        $fileMatch = [regex]::Match($block, '(?im)^file:\\s*(.+)')\n        if ($oldMatch.Success) { $oldLine = $oldMatch.Groups[1].Value.Trim() }\n        if ($newMatch.Success) { $newText = $newMatch.Groups[1].Value.Trim() }\n        if ($fileMatch.Success) { $fileLine = $fileMatch.Groups[1].Value.Trim() }\n        Write-Host \"[DEBUG] direct parse: old_line='$oldLine' file_line='$fileLine' new_text_len=$($newText.Length)\"\n    }","new_string":"    # Extract the MUTATION block content\n    # Strategy: find the triple-backtick block that follows \"### MUTATION\"\n    # We match: ### MUTATION + newline + ``` + content + ```\n    # Must handle cases where the content ITSELF contains ``` code blocks\n    $mutMatch = [regex]::Match($block, '(?s)### MUTATION\\s*\\n(.*?)\\n\\s*```\\s*$', [System.Text.RegularExpressions.RegexOptions]::Singleline)\n    if ($mutMatch.Success) {\n        # The opening ``` is right after ### MUTATION, and closing ``` ends the block\n        # Extract everything between the first ``` after MUTATION and the final ```\n        $innerStart = $block.IndexOf('```', $block.IndexOf('### MUTATION'))\n        $innerContent = $block.Substring($innerStart + 3)  # skip the opening ```\n        # Find the last ``` as the closing fence\n        $lastTripleBacktick = $innerContent.LastIndexOf('```')\n        if ($lastTripleBacktick -gt 0) {\n            $codeContent = $innerContent.Substring(0, $lastTripleBacktick).Trim()\n        } else {\n            $codeContent = $innerContent.Trim()\n        }\n        Write-Host \"[DEBUG] codeContent extracted, length: $($codeContent.Length)\"\n        # Parse fields - key: value on each line\n        $lines = $codeContent -split \"`n\"\n        $oldLine = \"\"; $newText = \"\"; $fileLine = \"\"\n        foreach ($line in $lines) {\n            if ($line -match '^old_text:\\s*(.+)') { $oldLine = $Matches[1].Trim() }\n            if ($line -match '^new_text:\\s*(.+)') { $newText = $Matches[1].Trim() }\n            if ($line -match '^file:\\s*(.+)') { $fileLine = $Matches[1].Trim() }\n        }\n        Write-Host \"[DEBUG] parsed: old_line='$oldLine' file_line='$fileLine' new_text_len=$($newText.Length)\"\n    } else {\n        Write-Host \"[DEBUG] outer MUTATION block regex failed. Trying simpler parse...\"\n        # Last-resort: find file: and old_text: anywhere in the MUTATION block\n        $fileMatch = [regex]::Match($block, 'file:\\s*([^\\s\\n]+)')\n        $oldMatch = [regex]::Match($block, 'old_text:\\s*\\(([^)]+)\\)')\n        if ($fileMatch.Success) { $fileLine = $fileMatch.Groups[1].Value.Trim() }\n        if ($oldMatch.Success) { $oldLine = $oldMatch.Groups[1].Value.Trim() }\n        # For new_text, find the text after \"new_text:\" until we hit \"file:\"\n        $ntMatch = [regex]::Match($block, 'new_text:\\s*([^\\n]+(?:\\n(?![^\\s]+:)[^\\n]+)*)', [System.Text.RegularExpressions.RegexOptions]::Multiline)\n        if ($ntMatch.Success) { $newText = $ntMatch.Groups[1].Value.Trim() }\n        Write-Host \"[DEBUG] fallback parse: old_line='$oldLine' file_line='$fileLine' new_text_len=$($newText.Length)\"\n    }"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":95378,"output":1783,"cacheRead":13731,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":110892,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774282004741}}
