{"type":"message","id":"c34952b5","parentId":"13683674","timestamp":"2026-03-23T16:07:52.023Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Wait, I'm overcomplicating this. Let me think about the actual structure of the LLM output:\n\n```\n### MUTATION\n```\nold_text: (new file)\nnew_text: # Title\n## Section\nSome content with `code` in it\n```\n```\n\nThe triple backticks after MUTATION open the code block. Then the content is everything until the closing triple backticks. The problem is that the content itself can contain triple backticks (since the LLM is writing markdown).\n\nA better approach: match from `### MUTATION` to the LAST ` ``` ` in the document. Or: find the ` ``` ` that immediately follows `### MUTATION` (opening fence) and the ` ``` ` at the end of the block.\n \nSo I need to find the first ``` after ### MUTATION, then work backwards to confirm it starts a line, then locate the closing ``` that ends the block. In my PowerShell code, I'm using the index of ### MUTATION to find where the block starts, then looking for the first ``` that follows it to mark the opening fence.\n\nActually, this approach is getting messy. Let me step back—the core issue is that I'm trying to extract a MUTATION block that looks like:\n\n```\n### MUTATION\n```\ncontent with possibly more ``` inside\n```\n```\n\nBut I need to handle the case where the content itself contains triple backticks. A simpler strategy would be to match from the opening ``` after ### MUTATION through to the final ``` that closes the block, accounting for the fact that the content between them might have nested code fences. Let me reconsider the regex pattern itself.\n\nThe real problem with `(?s)```\\s*\\n(.*?)\\n``` ` is that `.*?` stops at the first ` ``` ` it encounters, which could be one of many in the content. I need a greedy approach instead that matches everything between the opening and closing fences. A better pattern would use `.*` to consume everything possible, then work backwards from the end to find the actual closing fence:\n\n```powershell\n$codeBlockMatch = [regex]::Match($block, '(?s)```\\s*\\n(.*)\\n``` ')\n```\n\nBut this risks being too greedy. Let me test this simpler approach first before adding complexity.","thinkingSignature":"09f0f0f19f2f5d3c68c5e99a38c84a5ce236a0b9c43ec33123c263afd525f573"},{"type":"text","text":"Actually let me simplify - use a greedy match which should work if the closing ``` is at the end:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_0ysryqnqa3bc_1","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\pulse.ps1","oldText":"    # Extract the MUTATION block content\n    # Strategy: find the triple-backtick block that follows \"### MUTATION\"\n    # We match: ### MUTATION + newline + ``` + content + ```\n    # Must handle cases where the content ITSELF contains ``` code blocks\n    $mutMatch = [regex]::Match($block, '(?s)### MUTATION\\s*\\n(.*?)\\n\\s*```\\s*$', [System.Text.RegularExpressions.RegexOptions]::Singleline)\n    if ($mutMatch.Success) {\n        # The opening ``` is right after ### MUTATION, and closing ``` ends the block\n        # Extract everything between the first ``` after MUTATION and the final ```\n        $innerStart = $block.IndexOf('```', $block.IndexOf('### MUTATION'))\n        $innerContent = $block.Substring($innerStart + 3)  # skip the opening ```\n        # Find the last ``` as the closing fence\n        $lastTripleBacktick = $innerContent.LastIndexOf('```')\n        if ($lastTripleBacktick -gt 0) {\n            $codeContent = $innerContent.Substring(0, $lastTripleBacktick).Trim()\n        } else {\n            $codeContent = $innerContent.Trim()\n        }\n        Write-Host \"[DEBUG] codeContent extracted, length: $($codeContent.Length)\"\n        # Parse fields - key: value on each line\n        $lines = $codeContent -split \"`n\"\n        $oldLine = \"\"; $newText = \"\"; $fileLine = \"\"\n        foreach ($line in $lines) {\n            if ($line -match '^old_text:\\s*(.+)') { $oldLine = $Matches[1].Trim() }\n            if ($line -match '^new_text:\\s*(.+)') { $newText = $Matches[1].Trim() }\n            if ($line -match '^file:\\s*(.+)') { $fileLine = $Matches[1].Trim() }\n        }\n        Write-Host \"[DEBUG] parsed: old_line='$oldLine' file_line='$fileLine' new_text_len=$($newText.Length)\"\n    } else {\n        Write-Host \"[DEBUG] outer MUTATION block regex failed. Trying simpler parse...\"\n        # Last-resort: find file: and old_text: anywhere in the MUTATION block\n        $fileMatch = [regex]::Match($block, 'file:\\s*([^\\s\\n]+)')\n        $oldMatch = [regex]::Match($block, 'old_text:\\s*\\(([^)]+)\\)')\n        if ($fileMatch.Success) { $fileLine = $fileMatch.Groups[1].Value.Trim() }\n        if ($oldMatch.Success) { $oldLine = $oldMatch.Groups[1].Value.Trim() }\n        # For new_text, find the text after \"new_text:\" until we hit \"file:\"\n        $ntMatch = [regex]::Match($block, 'new_text:\\s*([^\\n]+(?:\\n(?![^\\s]+:)[^\\n]+)*)', [System.Text.RegularExpressions.RegexOptions]::Multiline)\n        if ($ntMatch.Success) { $newText = $ntMatch.Groups[1].Value.Trim() }\n        Write-Host \"[DEBUG] fallback parse: old_line='$oldLine' file_line='$fileLine' new_text_len=$($newText.Length)\"\n    }","new_string":"    # Extract MUTATION block - greedy match from opening ``` to last ```\n    # (content between may contain embedded ``` which we accept as part of new_text)\n    $mutBlockStart = $block.IndexOf('```')\n    if ($mutBlockStart -ge 0) {\n        $afterOpening = $block.Substring($mutBlockStart + 3)\n        $lastTripleBacktick = $afterOpening.LastIndexOf('```')\n        if ($lastTripleBacktick -gt 0) {\n            $codeContent = $afterOpening.Substring(0, $lastTripleBacktick).Trim()\n            Write-Host \"[DEBUG] extracted codeContent: $($codeContent.Length) chars\"\n            # Parse key: value lines\n            $lines = $codeContent -split \"`n\"\n            $oldLine = \"\"; $newText = \"\"; $fileLine = \"\"\n            foreach ($ln in $lines) {\n                if ($ln -match '^old_text:\\s*(.+)') { $oldLine = $Matches[1].Trim() }\n                if ($ln -match '^new_text:\\s*(.+)') { $newText = $Matches[1].Trim() }\n                if ($ln -match '^file:\\s*(.+)') { $fileLine = $Matches[1].Trim() }\n            }\n            Write-Host \"[DEBUG] parsed: old_line='$oldLine' file_line='$fileLine' new_text_len=$($newText.Length)\"\n        } else {\n            Write-Host \"[DEBUG] no closing ``` found\"\n        }\n    } else {\n        Write-Host \"[DEBUG] no opening ``` found\"\n    }"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":95261,"output":1625,"cacheRead":13731,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":110617,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774282035126}}
