 which doesn't align with the block starting at position 1862.\n\nWait, I think I see the issue. The Python script was reading from `.llm_response.txt`, but that file gets overwritten each time `call_llm.py` runs. The previous pulse output was 4235 characters, but my Python test showed 3563 characters—so the file changed between runs. The current pulse has 4806 characters, and I need to trace back which execution produced which file to understand the size mismatch.\n\nLooking at the actual content: the block starts at position 1862 in the current file, the first backtick appears at position 13 within that block (global position 1875), and there's only a single backtick on the line with `old_text:`, not the triple backticks I initially expected.\n\nThe issue is clear now—when I strip the first backtick as the opening delimiter, I'm removing the 'o' from `old_text:`, leaving `ld_text:` instead. The parser then fails to find the old_text pattern and marks it as empty, so the mutation never applies.\n\nThe solution is to skip the opening backtick AND the immediately following newline character, since the content format is `### MUTATION\\n`\\nold_text:...` — the backtick followed by a newline that gets consumed during extraction.\n\nBut actually, the real problem is simpler: I should just look for the triple backtick sequence instead of assuming a single backtick marks the boundaries. Let me reconsider the structure of the mutation block to figure out where it actually starts and ends. I'm realizing the triple backtick sequence is actually a single Unicode character (U+201C, the left double quotation mark), not three separate backticks—which is why the regex pattern looking for three individual backticks wasn't matching anything.\n\nThe issue is that the Python `repr()` output was displaying this as ` ``` `, making it look like three ASCII backticks when it's actually one Unicode character. So when the code searches for the triple backtick pattern using `'```'`, it's not finding anything because the actual character in the text is the Unicode left double quotation mark instead.\n\nLooking at the byte inspection, the sequence at position 16 is `0x60 0x60 0x60` which are three literal ASCII backticks, but then at position 4808 there are only two backticks in the closing fence instead of three. So the file has an unmatched fence structure—three opening backticks but only two closing backticks. The closing fence is incomplete — just two backticks instead of three. Looking at the byte positions more carefully: the opening ``` starts at 1862+16=1878 and spans 3 bytes (1878-1880), followed by \\r\\n, so the actual content begins at 1882. The closing ``` starts at 4808 and should span 3 bytes, but the file size of 4808 only goes up to index 4807, which means either the file is truncated or there's a mismatch between what the byte inspection shows and the actual file size. Looking at the byte positions more carefully: the opening ``` starts at byte 1878 (three bytes: 0x60 0x60 0x60), which is right after the \\r\\n sequence following \"### MUTATION\". The closing ``` would then be at byte 4808, but the file only contains 4808 bytes total (indices 0-4807), so there aren't enough bytes to hold another triple backtick sequence after the last byte. The closing fence only has 2 backticks in the actual data, so trying to match 3 backticks fails and returns -1. Then when I search for the opening single backtick, I find it at position 13 in the block—which is just the first backtick of the triple sequence, not a separate delimiter. This means I'm accidentally stripping content from within the triple backticks instead of properly isolating the code block. I need to search for the triple backtick sequence instead of a single backtick to properly extract the MUTATION content.","thinkingSignature":"d8f6f15b85549b034ddb73467789878b796f72e605561c969ef40ae382b11c6a"},{"type":"text","text":"Found it. The actual byte inspection shows the opening fence is **