{"type":"message","id":"e9460f98","parentId":"bcf18375","timestamp":"2026-03-23T17:25:48.615Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The file uses `\\xce\\xbb` which is UTF-8 encoding of `λ` (Greek lambda). And then the inner code block uses `\\xce\\xbb` for the lambda in the formula. The issue is that the LLM response contains a nested code block with triple backticks, and the outer MUTATION block is also using triple backticks. The regex for the outer block uses `.IndexOf('`')` which finds a SINGLE backtick, not triple.\n\nBut looking at this output: `b'### MUTATION\\r\\n```\\r\\nold_text: (new file)\\r\\nnew_text:` — the outer block DOES use triple backticks. \n\nThe problem is that my extraction logic is pulling from the wrong code block. When I look for the first backtick after `### MUTATION`, I'm getting the first backtick of the triple backtick sequence, then adding 3 to skip past it — but that's actually skipping past the first character of the triple-backtick opener itself, not the whole sequence.\n\nWait, let me reconsider. If the sequence is ``` ` ` ` ``` (three backticks), then `IndexOf('`')` finds position 0, and `Substring(0 + 1)` gives me the remaining two backticks plus the content. Then `LastIndexOf('`')` on that substring would give me the position of the second backtick in that sequence, which means I'm only extracting content with a closing sequence of two backticks instead of three.\n\nActually, I think the real issue is that the outer MUTATION block has triple backticks, but the content inside contains another set of triple backticks — like a code example within the MUTATION itself. So my greedy extraction is capturing too much, pulling in the inner triple backticks as if they were the closing fence. Looking at the extraction logic more carefully, when I find the first backtick at position 0 in the MUTATION block, I grab everything after it and search for the last backtick. With triple backticks followed by newlines, that last backtick is actually part of the first triple-backtick closer on its own line—so I'm capturing just `` ` `` instead of the complete closing fence. The real issue is that I need to match the actual triple backtick sequence, not just individual backticks scattered throughout the block.","thinkingSignature":"75540fb9a92b625ebdb8a806cece3f8b388d4020136dd0274ea445b8ce5b41b3"},{"type":"text","text":"The backtick extraction logic is off — it's finding single backticks inside code examples, not the triple-fence. Let me fix with a proper regex:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_qfoucjz9zs87_1","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\pulse.ps1","oldText":"    # Extract MUTATION block - greedy match from opening ` to last `\n    # The LLM uses single backticks as fence markers (confirmed by byte inspection)\n    $mutBlockStart = $block.IndexOf('`')\n    if ($mutBlockStart -ge 0) {\n        $afterOpening = $block.Substring($mutBlockStart + 1)\n        $lastSingleBacktick = $afterOpening.LastIndexOf('`')\n        if ($lastSingleBacktick -gt 0) {\n            $codeContent = $afterOpening.Substring(0, $lastSingleBacktick).Trim()\n            Write-Host \"[DEBUG] extracted codeContent: $($codeContent.Length) chars\"\n            # Parse key: value lines\n            $lines = $codeContent -split \"`n\"\n            $oldLine = \"\"; $newText = \"\"; $fileLine = \"\"\n            foreach ($ln in $lines) {\n                if ($ln -match '^old_text:\\s*(.+)') { $oldLine = $Matches[1].Trim() }\n                if ($ln -match '^new_text:\\s*(.+)') { $newText = $Matches[1].Trim() }\n                if ($ln -match '^file:\\s*(.+)') { $fileLine = $Matches[1].Trim() }\n            }\n            Write-Host \"[DEBUG] parsed: old_line='$oldLine' file_line='$fileLine' new_text_len=$($newText.Length)\"\n        } else {\n            Write-Host \"[DEBUG] no closing backtick found\"\n        }\n    } else {\n        Write-Host \"[DEBUG] no opening backtick found\"\n    }","new_string":"    # Extract MUTATION block content between triple-backtick fences\n    # The LLM wraps the block in ``` ... ```\n    # We need to find the triple-backtick fence after \"### MUTATION\" and grab content until the next ```\n    $tripleBacktick = '```'\n    $mutHeaderIdx = $block.IndexOf('### MUTATION')\n    if ($mutHeaderIdx -ge 0) {\n        $afterHeader = $block.Substring($mutHeaderIdx + 13)  # skip \"### MUTATION\"\n        $fenceStart = $afterHeader.IndexOf($tripleBacktick)\n        if ($fenceStart -ge 0) {\n            $contentStart = $fenceStart + 3  # skip the opening ```\n            $afterFence = $afterHeader.Substring($contentStart)\n            $fenceEnd = $afterFence.IndexOf($tripleBacktick)\n            if ($fenceEnd -gt 0) {\n                $codeContent = $afterFence.Substring(0, $fenceEnd).Trim()\n                Write-Host \"[DEBUG] extracted codeContent: $($codeContent.Length) chars\"\n                # Parse key: value lines (handle multi-line new_text)\n                $lines = $codeContent -split \"`n\"\n                $oldLine = \"\"; $newText = \"\"; $fileLine = \"\"; $inNewText = $false; $newTextLines = @()\n                foreach ($ln in $lines) {\n                    if ($ln -match '^old_text:\\s*(.+)') { $oldLine = $Matches[1].Trim() }\n                    elseif ($ln -match '^file:\\s*(.+)') { $fileLine = $Matches[1].Trim(); $inNewText = $false }\n                    elseif ($ln -match '^new_text:\\s*(.+)') {\n                        $inNewText = $true\n                        $newTextLines += $Matches[1].Trim()\n                    }\n                    elseif ($inNewText) {\n                        # Continuation of new_text until we hit file: or old_text:\n                        if ($ln -match '^old_text:' -or $ln -match '^file:') { $inNewText = $false }\n                        else { $newTextLines += $ln }\n                    }\n                }\n                $newText = $newTextLines -join \"`n\"\n                Write-Host \"[DEBUG] parsed: old_line='$oldLine' file_line='$fileLine' new_text_len=$($newText.Length)\"\n            } else {\n                Write-Host \"[DEBUG] no closing ``` found\"\n            }\n        } else {\n            Write-Host \"[DEBUG] no opening ``` found\"\n        }\n    }"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":91832,"output":1496,"cacheRead":13731,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":107059,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774286723301}}
