{"type":"message","id":"42b4298c","parentId":"c2c1a752","timestamp":"2026-03-23T17:38:08.342Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_u0z7gjjwl0v0_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Done\r\nPositions of ``` in block: [484, 545]\r\n\r\nPosition 0 (484): context=''ula\\n\\n```\\n�(puls''\r\nPosition 1 (545): context=''urr)\\n```\\n\\nWhere''\r\n\r\n=== FULL MUTATION BLOCK ===\r\n### MUTATION\r\n`\r\nold_text: (new file)\r\nnew_text: # Significance Scoring for Pulse Content\r\n# Derived from COMPRESSION-CAUSAL DUALITY hypothesis (2026-03-23)\r\n\r\n## Core Hypothesis\r\n> Significance = variance across sessions (what changes)\r\n> Invariance = stability across sessions (what persists)\r\n\r\nA pulse segment is **significant** if its representation changes between sessions.\r\nA pulse segment is **invariant** if its representation persists across sessions.\r\n\r\n## Significance Score Formula\r\n\r\n```\r\n�(pulse_segm\r\n\r\n=== END ===\r\n\r\n=== CONTENT (positions 487 to 545, 58 chars) ===\r\n\r\n�(pulse_segment) = 1 - cosine_similarity(v_prev, v_curr)"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":716,"aggregated":"Done\r\nPositions of ``` in block: [484, 545]\r\n\r\nPosition 0 (484): context=''ula\\n\\n```\\n�(puls''\r\nPosition 1 (545): context=''urr)\\n```\\n\\nWhere''\r\n\r\n=== FULL MUTATION BLOCK ===\r\n### MUTATION\r\n`\r\nold_text: (new file)\r\nnew_text: # Significance Scoring for Pulse Content\r\n# Derived from COMPRESSION-CAUSAL DUALITY hypothesis (2026-03-23)\r\n\r\n## Core Hypothesis\r\n> Significance = variance across sessions (what changes)\r\n> Invariance = stability across sessions (what persists)\r\n\r\nA pulse segment is **significant** if its representation changes between sessions.\r\nA pulse segment is **invariant** if its representation persists across sessions.\r\n\r\n## Significance Score Formula\r\n\r\n```\r\n�(pulse_segm\r\n\r\n=== END ===\r\n\r\n=== CONTENT (positions 487 to 545, 58 chars) ===\r\n\r\n�(pulse_segment) = 1 - cosine_similarity(v_prev, v_curr)","cwd":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774287488313}}
{"type":"message","id":"d557f0fd","parentId":"42b4298c","timestamp":"2026-03-23T17:38:49.355Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see the full picture:\n\nThe MUTATION block starts with:\n```\n### MUTATION\n`\nold_text: (new file)\nnew_text: # Significance Scoring for Pulse Content\n...\n## Significance Score Formula\n\n`\n```\nsigma(pulse_segment) = 1 - cosine_similarity(v_prev, v_curr)\n`\n\nWhere do we go from here...\n\n```\n\nSo the structure is:\n- `### MUTATION\\n` (10 chars)\n- `` ` `` (1 backtick, SINGLE backtick)\n- content...\n\nWait, looking at position 484's context: `ula\\n\\n\\`\\`\\`\\n�(puls` — this shows that position 484 is a triple backtick (`\\`\\`\\``)! The context shows `\\`\\`\\`` at position 484. \n\nAnd position 545: `urr)\\n\\`\\`\\`\\n\\nWhere'` — another triple backtick at 545.\n\nBut wait — the content between positions 487 and 545 is only 58 characters: `�(pulse_segment) = 1 - cosine_similarity(v_prev, v_curr)`. That's way too short. So the first triple backtick is at 484, and content starts at 487 after skipping the three backticks, ending at 545 where the next triple backtick appears.\n\nThe problem is that `block[487:545]` only captures 58 characters, but the actual content should span from the opening backtick through to where the closing backtick appears at 545. I need to trace through this more carefully — if position 484 is the start of `\\`\\`\\``, then position 487 should be right after it, but the extraction is cutting off too early. So position 484 starts the triple backtick itself, which means `block[487:545]` extracts 58 characters of actual content. That leaves position 545 as the start of the closing triple backtick, with the content between them being just that formula string.\n\nBut the full block shows there's content after position 545 — specifically the closing fence and the `Where do we go from here...` part. This suggests there are actually multiple fence pairs, not just one. Looking at the full block starting from `### MUTATION\\n`, there's an opening backtick followed by `old_text: (new file)` and then `new_text:` on the next line, which means I need to reconsider where the actual code fence boundaries are. Looking at the debug output more carefully, position 484 appears to be the triple backtick that opens the code block, and the `ola` at position 481-483 is the end of a formula that was already cut off mid-word.\n\nThe content I'm extracting between positions 487 and 545 is just `sigma(pulse_segment) = 1 - cosine_similarity(v_prev, v_curr)` — 58 characters — which is the Significance Score Formula nested inside the new_text field. This means the LLM wrapped the formula in a code block within the new_text value itself, not that the entire new_text ends there.\n\nSo when I search for `old_text:`, `new_text:`, and `file:` in this extracted content, `old_match` comes back empty because `old_text: (new file)` isn't there, `new_match` matches but only captures up to the embedded code block, and `file_match` finds the actual file path at the end. The real problem is that my extraction logic is stopping at the first closing triple backtick it encounters, which is actually part of an inner code block within the new_text field, not the outer block boundary I should be using.\n\nLooking at where the actual closing fence is in the full text — it appears after the `file:` line, meaning my extraction ends too early and I'm missing the actual file path reference that comes after.\n\nThe solution is to skip the first closing fence I find (since it's inside the new_text value) and instead find the second one, which should be the actual outer closing delimiter. Rather than trying to handle fence nesting, I should just extract the three fields directly using regex and handle new_text as potentially multiline content.","thinkingSignature":"73ae04325988393839ee190b95bbccbf66dec85f05a56ed996012e806831ca9d"},{"type":"text","text":"The closing ``` at position 545 is INSIDE `new_text` (nested formula). The real closing fence is the SECOND one. The `rfind` finds the first (wrong) one. Let me fix with a smarter approach:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_7ut1ubw3ypil_1","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\parse_mutation.py","old_string":"mut_start = raw.find(\"### MUTATION\")\nif mut_start < 0:\n    print(\"ERROR: no MUTATION block found\", file=sys.stderr)\n    sys.exit(1)\n\nblock = raw[mut_start:]\n\n# Strategy: find the first code fence content (between the first ``` and the LAST ``` in the block)\n# The LLM sometimes nests code blocks, so we find the LAST triple-backtick pair\ntb = \"```\"\nfence1 = block.find(tb)\nif fence1 < 0:\n    print(\"ERROR: no opening fence\", file=sys.stderr)\n    sys.exit(1)\n\n# Search for the closing fence: find the LAST occurrence of ``` followed by newline or end\nsearch_from = fence1 + 3\n# Find the last ``` in the block (the closing fence)\nlast_tb = block.rfind(tb)\nif last_tb <= fence1:\n    print(\"ERROR: no closing fence\", file=sys.stderr)\n    sys.exit(1)\n\ncode_content = block[fence1 + 3:last_tb].strip()\nprint(f\"DEBUG: code_content length={len(code_content)}\", file=sys.stderr)\nprint(f\"DEBUG: first 100: {repr(code_content[:100])}\", file=sys.stderr)\n\n# Now parse the fields from the code content\n# old_text: on its own line\nold_match = re.search(r'^old_text:\\s*(.+)', code_content, re.MULTILINE)\nold_text = old_match.group(1).strip() if old_match else \"\"\n\n# file: might be inside the code content OR after the closing fence in the raw block\nfile_match = re.search(r'^file:\\s*(.+)', code_content, re.MULTILINE)\nfile_text = file_match.group(1).strip() if file_match else \"\"\n\n# If file not found inside, search in the raw block after the MUTATION section\nif not file_text:\n    # Search for file: in the block AFTER the last closing fence\n    after_close = block[last_tb + 3:]\n    file_match2 = re.search(r'^file:\\s*(.+)', after_close, re.MULTILINE)\n    if file_match2:\n        file_text = file_match2.group(1).strip()\n\n# new_text: is multiline — from \"new_text: \" to the line before \"file:\" or \"old_text:\"\nnew_text_lines = []\nin_new_text = False\nfor line in code_content.split('\\n'):\n    if re.match(r'^old_text:', line) or re.match(r'^file:', line):\n        in_new_text = False\n    if in_new_text:\n        new_text_lines.append(line)\n    m = re.match(r'^new_text:\\s*(.*)', line)\n    if m:\n        in_new_text = True\n        val = m.group(1).strip()\n        if val:\n            new_text_lines.append(val)\n\nnew_text = '\\n'.join(new_text_lines)\n\nprint(f\"DEBUG: old={repr(old_text)}\", file=sys.stderr)\nprint(f\"DEBUG: file={repr(file_text)}\", file=sys.stderr)\nprint(f\"DEBUG: new_text len={len(new_text)}\", file=sys.stderr)\n\n# Output: old_text|new_text|file\n# Use a separator that won't appear in content: |||\noutput = f\"{old_text}|||{new_text}|||{file_text}\"\nsys.stdout.write(output)","new_string":"mut_start = raw.find(\"### MUTATION\")\nif mut_start < 0:\n    print(\"ERROR: no MUTATION block found\", file=sys.stderr)\n    sys.exit(1)\n\nblock = raw[mut_start:]\n\n# Find ALL triple-backtick positions\ntb = \"```\"\npositions = []\nsearch_from = 0\nwhile True:\n    p = block.find(tb, search_from)\n    if p == -1:\n        break\n    positions.append(p)\n    search_from = p + 3\n\nif len(positions) < 2:\n    print(\"ERROR: fewer than 2 fences found\", file=sys.stderr)\n    sys.exit(1)\n\n# Use the FIRST and SECOND-TO-LAST fences as the outer block boundaries\n# (skip nested fences inside new_text content)\nopening_fence = positions[0]\nclosing_fence = positions[-1]  # last one\nopening_content_start = opening_fence + 3\n\n# Extract raw content between the outer fences\nouter_content = block[opening_content_start:closing_fence]\nprint(f\"DEBUG: {len(positions)} fences found, outer block={len(outer_content)} chars\", file=sys.stderr)\n\n# Now parse fields directly from the raw block (before fence removal)\n# We need old_text: and new_text: from the content, and file: from content or after\n# Strategy: find the FIRST occurrence of each field in the OUTER content\nouter_block = outer_content  # content between first ``` and last ```\n\n# Extract old_text: - find the line starting with \"old_text:\" within outer_content\nold_match = re.search(r'^old_text:\\s*(.+)$', outer_block, re.MULTILINE)\nold_text = old_match.group(1).strip() if old_match else \"\"\n\n# Extract file: - it may be in the outer_content OR after the closing fence\nfile_match = re.search(r'^file:\\s*(.+)$', outer_block, re.MULTILINE)\nfile_text = file_match.group(1).strip() if file_match else \"\"\nif not file_text:\n    after_close = block[closing_fence + 3:]\n    file_match2 = re.search(r'^file:\\s*(.+)$', after_close, re.MULTILINE)\n    if file_match2:\n        file_text = file_match2.group(1).strip()\n\n# Extract new_text: - multiline, from \"new_text:\" until \"file:\" or \"old_text:\" or closing fence\nnew_text_match = re.search(r'^new_text:\\s*(.*)$', outer_block, re.MULTILINE)\nif new_text_match:\n    # new_text: starts at new_text_match.end()\n    # It ends at the next \"file:\" or \"old_text:\" or end of outer_block\n    new_text_start = new_text_match.end()\n    # Find the next field or closing content\n    next_old = re.search(r'^old_text:', outer_block[new_text_start:], re.MULTILINE)\n    next_file = re.search(r'^file:', outer_block[new_text_start:], re.MULTILINE)\n    end_pos = len(outer_block)\n    if next_old:\n        end_pos = min(end_pos, new_text_start + next_old.start())\n    if next_file:\n        end_pos = min(end_pos, new_text_start + next_file.start())\n    new_text = outer_block[new_text_start:end_pos].strip()\nelse:\n    new_text = \"\"\n\nprint(f\"DEBUG: old={repr(old_text[:50] if old_text else '')}\", file=sys.stderr)\nprint(f\"DEBUG: file={repr(file_text)}\", file=sys.stderr)\nprint(f\"DEBUG: new_text len={len(new_text)}, first 100: {repr(new_text[:100])}\", file=sys.stderr)\n\n# Write result to JSON file\nresult_file = os.path.join(os.path.dirname(__file__), \".mutation_parse_result.json\")\nresult = {\"old\": old_text, \"new\": new_text, \"file\": file_text}\nwith open(result_file, \"w\", encoding=\"utf-8\") as f:\n    json.dump(result, f, ensure_ascii=False)\nprint(f\"Result written to {result_file}\", file=sys.stderr)\nsys.stdout.write(\"OK\")"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":80833,"output":2570,"cacheRead":13731,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":97134,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774287488354}}
{"type":"message","id":"8d10214f","parentId":"d557f0fd","timestamp":"2026-03-23T17:38:49.451Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_7ut1ubw3ypil_1","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\n  \"status\": \"error\",\n  \"tool\": \"edit\",\n  \"error\": \"Could not find the exact text in C:\\\\Users\\\\Zwmar\\\\.openclaw\\\\sandbox\\\\parse_mutation.py. The old text must match exactly including all whitespace and newlines.\"\n}"}],"details":{"status":"error","tool":"edit","error":"Could not find the exact text in C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\parse_mutation.py. The old text must match exactly including all whitespace and newlines."},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774287529430}}
{"type":"message","id":"0e44e2a7","parentId":"8d10214f","timestamp":"2026-03-23T17:38:52.623Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The file was already modified when I tested it. Let me read it first to see the current state.","thinkingSignature":"a59816c0e4c95a6d6139705e95cf7899af241204f49990172432dcc0e588d27c"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_6q1ssip88by3_1","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\parse_mutation.py"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":83477,"output":63,"cacheRead":13731,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":97271,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774287529462}}
{"type":"message","id":"acf14922","parentId":"0e44e2a7","timestamp":"2026-03-23T17:38:52.748Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_6q1ssip88by3_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\"\"\"\nparse_mutation.py — Extracts mutation fields from LLM raw response\nWrites to stdout: old_text|new_text|file\n\"\"\"\nimport sys, re, os, json\n\nresponse_file = sys.argv[1] if len(sys.argv) > 1 else os.path.join(os.path.dirname(__file__), \".llm_response.txt\")\nwith open(response_file, \"r\", encoding=\"utf-8\") as f:\n    raw = f.read()\n\nmut_start = raw.find(\"### MUTATION\")\nif mut_start < 0:\n    print(\"ERROR: no MUTATION block found\", file=sys.stderr)\n    sys.exit(1)\n\nblock = raw[mut_start:]\n\n# Strategy: find the first code fence content (between the first ``` and the LAST ``` in the block)\n# The LLM sometimes nests code blocks, so we find the LAST triple-backtick pair\ntb = \"```\"\nfence1 = block.find(tb)\nif fence1 < 0:\n    print(\"ERROR: no opening fence\", file=sys.stderr)\n    sys.exit(1)\n\n# Search for the closing fence: find the LAST occurrence of ``` followed by newline or end\nsearch_from = fence1 + 3\n# Find the last ``` in the block (the closing fence)\nlast_tb = block.rfind(tb)\nif last_tb <= fence1:\n    print(\"ERROR: no closing fence\", file=sys.stderr)\n    sys.exit(1)\n\ncode_content = block[fence1 + 3:last_tb].strip()\nprint(f\"DEBUG: code_content length={len(code_content)}\", file=sys.stderr)\nprint(f\"DEBUG: first 100: {repr(code_content[:100])}\", file=sys.stderr)\n\n# Now parse the fields from the code content\n# old_text: on its own line\nold_match = re.search(r'^old_text:\\s*(.+)', code_content, re.MULTILINE)\nold_text = old_match.group(1).strip() if old_match else \"\"\n\n# file: might be inside the code content OR after the closing fence in the raw block\nfile_match = re.search(r'^file:\\s*(.+)', code_content, re.MULTILINE)\nfile_text = file_match.group(1).strip() if file_match else \"\"\n\n# If file not found inside, search in the raw block after the MUTATION section\nif not file_text:\n    # Search for file: in the block AFTER the last closing fence\n    after_close = block[last_tb + 3:]\n    file_match2 = re.search(r'^file:\\s*(.+)', after_close, re.MULTILINE)\n    if file_match2:\n        file_text = file_match2.group(1).strip()\n\n# new_text: is multiline — from \"new_text: \" to the line before \"file:\" or \"old_text:\"\nnew_text_lines = []\nin_new_text = False\nfor line in code_content.split('\\n'):\n    if re.match(r'^old_text:', line) or re.match(r'^file:', line):\n        in_new_text = False\n    if in_new_text:\n        new_text_lines.append(line)\n    m = re.match(r'^new_text:\\s*(.*)', line)\n    if m:\n        in_new_text = True\n        val = m.group(1).strip()\n        if val:\n            new_text_lines.append(val)\n\nnew_text = '\\n'.join(new_text_lines)\n\nprint(f\"DEBUG: old={repr(old_text)}\", file=sys.stderr)\nprint(f\"DEBUG: file={repr(file_text)}\", file=sys.stderr)\nprint(f\"DEBUG: new_text len={len(new_text)}\", file=sys.stderr)\n\n# Output: write result to file (avoids stdout encoding issues)\nresult_file = os.path.join(os.path.dirname(__file__), \".mutation_parse_result.json\")\nresult = {\"old\": old_text, \"new\": new_text, \"file\": file_text}\nwith open(result_file, \"w\", encoding=\"utf-8\") as f:\n    json.dump(result, f, ensure_ascii=False)\nprint(f\"Result written to {result_file}\", file=sys.stderr)\nsys.stdout.write(\"OK\")\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774287532716}}
{"type":"message","id":"2ce0f056","parentId":"acf14922","timestamp":"2026-03-23T17:39:15.368Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK, the issue is clear now. The current code:\n1. Finds `fence1` (first triple backtick) and `last_tb` (last triple backtick = position 545)\n2. Extracts `block[fence1+3:last_tb]` = only 58 chars of content (the formula)\n3. That's because the last triple backtick in the block is at position 545, which is the nested closing fence inside new_text\n\nThe real outer closing fence is the SECOND-LAST triple backtick. But actually, looking at the structure:\n\n```\n### MUTATION\n`                ← opening (single backtick)\n\n\n```\n\nWait — let me re-examine. The debug shows the content between the first ``` at position 484 and the last ``` at position 545 is only 58 chars. But the full MUTATION block shows there's more content after position 545 (after the closing ```). This means the CLOSING fence is AFTER position 545, which would be at the second-to-last position if there are multiple fences. Looking at the context: position 484 is the FIRST ``` (opening), and position 545 is somewhere inside the content, not the actual closing fence. The real closing fence must be further down in the block.\n\nThe debug output shows position 545's context ends with `urr)\\n\\`\\`\\`\\n\\nWhere` — so that's actually the closing fence, not a middle one. If there are only 2 fences total, then position 484 opens and 545 closes the outer block, which means the 58-character content between them is all there is. But the full MUTATION block clearly shows `old_text: (new file)` followed by `new_text: # Significance Scoring...`, so something's not adding up with how the fences are being counted or positioned.\n\n```\n\npython\n# If file not found inside, search in the raw block after the MUTATION section\nif not file_text:\n    # Search for file: in the block AFTER the last closing fence\n    after_close = block[last_tb + 3:]\n```\n\nThe `after_close` logic looks correct — it should grab everything after position 545. But the regex isn't matching `file:` in that section, which suggests the actual closing fence might be positioned differently than I'm calculating, or the file reference is formatted differently than expected.\n\nLet me trace through the actual fence positions. If there are exactly 2 fences at 484 and 545, then `block[487:545]` gives me the 58-character formula content, and `block[548:]` should have the `file:` reference. But the debug output shows `### MUTATION\\n` followed by a single backtick, which means the opening fence isn't where I thought it was — I need to reconsider the exact positions and what the block structure actually contains.","thinkingSignature":"4495b7a8b2bca56ef7605d60ae7cbeabbabfd85e33f3510000c476494e60a7a0"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_b0xgx6uz3x3t_1","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\workspace\\debug_fence.py","content":"import sys, re\nsys.stdout.reconfigure(encoding='utf-8')\nwith open(r\"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\.llm_response.txt\", \"r\", encoding=\"utf-8\") as f:\n    raw = f.read()\n\nmut_start = raw.find(\"### MUTATION\")\nif mut_start < 0:\n    print(\"no MUTATION\")\n    sys.exit()\nblock = raw[mut_start:]\n\ntb = \"```\"\npositions = []\nsearch_from = 0\nwhile True:\n    p = block.find(tb, search_from)\n    if p == -1:\n        break\n    positions.append(p)\n    search_from = p + 1\n\nwith open(r\"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\workspace\\fence_debug.txt\", \"w\", encoding=\"utf-8\") as out:\n    out.write(f\"Fence positions: {positions}\\n\")\n    out.write(f\"Total fences: {len(positions)}\\n\\n\")\n    \n    # Show content at each position\n    for i, pos in enumerate(positions):\n        start = max(0, pos - 10)\n        end = min(len(block), pos + 10)\n        out.write(f\"Position {i} ({pos}): context='{repr(block[start:end])}'\\n\")\n    \n    # Show the outer block content (between