{"type":"message","id":"91d59ac3","parentId":"4e708b37","timestamp":"2026-03-23T17:39:42.675Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see it. The OUTER BLOCK CONTENT is only 58 chars — `sigma(pulse_segment) = 1 - cosine_similarity(v_prev, v_curr)` — which is the formula INSIDE the new_text value (the embedded code fence within the markdown).\n\nThe ACTUAL content between `### MUTATION` and the closing ` ``` ` (at position 545) is just that formula. The `old_text: (new file)`, `new_text: ...`, and `file: ...` are ALL AFTER the closing fence at position 545!\n\nThis means the LLM's format for MUTATION is:\n```\n### MUTATION\n`\nold_text: (new file)\n\n\nnew_text: # Significance Scoring...\n...\n```\nsigma formula\n```\nfile: research/SIGNIFICANCE-SCORING.md\n```\n\nWhere the first ``` opens an inline code span (single backtick), then the nested ``` ... ``` is a code block inside the value. But wait — the outer block spans from position 0 (the opening ```) to position 545 (the closing ```), and that's only the formula content, which means the field definitions must come after that closing fence.\n\nSo the structure is actually: the first ``` at position 0 is just an inline code span wrapping `old_text: (new file)`, then `new_text: ...` and the formula block follow, and the second ``` at position 545 closes that inline span. The closing fence of the entire MUTATION block must be at a different position — that's why the outer block content is only 58 characters long. The `block[opening+3:closing]` extracts only the formula, which is the content between the first pair of triple backticks. But the `file:` field is actually positioned after position 545, which means it's outside this extracted range.\n\nLooking at the position data more carefully: `block[487:545]` gives me `sigma(pulse_segment) = 1 - cosine_similarity(v_prev, v_curr)` (58 characters), and position 545 starts the closing triple backtick. This suggests there are only 2 triple backticks total in the block, but I'm trying to figure out where the closing fence actually is relative to where the file field appears. So the outer block spans positions 0-58, which means `old_text: (new file)` and `new_text: ...` are actually appearing after the closing triple backtick at position 545. This is strange—either the block itself doesn't have outer fences wrapping those lines, or they're positioned outside the block boundaries I identified. Let me reconsider whether `### MUTATION\\n` itself contains the fence markers I'm looking for.","thinkingSignature":"fae4c486cdbfa66904fe563d9c5cea8af0f554745d11e208f3c0e8235badd819"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_4yh869byetmg_1","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\workspace\\debug_fence.py","content":"import sys, re\nsys.stdout.reconfigure(encoding='utf-8')\nwith open(r\"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\.llm_response.txt\", \"r\", encoding=\"utf-8\") as f:\n    raw = f.read()\n\nmut_start = raw.find(\"### MUTATION\")\nif mut_start < 0:\n    print(\"no MUTATION\")\n    sys.exit()\nblock = raw[mut_start:]\n\n# Show first 400 chars of block\nwith open(r\"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\workspace\\fence_debug.txt\", \"w\", encoding=\"utf-8\") as out:\n    out.write(\"=== FIRST 400 CHARS OF BLOCK ===\\n\")\n    out.write(repr(block[:400]))\n    out.write(\"\\n\\n\")\n    \n    # Show chars 480-560\n    out.write(\"=== CHARS 480-560 ===\\n\")\n    out.write(repr(block[480:560]))\n    out.write(\"\\n\\n\")\n    \n    # Find ALL ``` positions\n    tb = \"```\"\n    pos = []\n    search = 0\n    while True:\n        p = block.find(tb, search)\n        if p == -1:\n            break\n        pos.append(p)\n        search = p + 1\n    out.write(f\"ALL ``` positions: {pos}\\n\")\n    \n    # Also check for single backticks\n    bk = \"`\"\n    bk_pos = []\n    search = 0\n    while True:\n        p = block.find(bk, search)\n        if p == -1:\n            break\n        bk_pos.ap