{"type":"message","id":"fba0ab75","parentId":"3b79117b","timestamp":"2026-03-23T17:42:04.527Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The LLM is now using TRIPLE backticks (```) for the MUTATION block, not single backticks. And the `old_text: (new file)` IS inside the triple backtick block. My parser was finding the FIRST triple backtick at position 0 of the block (after `### MUTATION\\n`), which would be the opening fence. And the LAST triple backtick would be at the end.\n\nBut wait — the structure is:```\n### MUTATION\n```\nold_text: (new file)\nnew_text: #!/usr/bin/env pwsh...\n```\n```\n\nSo the triple backticks at positions [0, ...] open and close the whole block. \n\nThe issue is that my parser treats the first triple backtick as the opening fence and extracts everything between the first and last instances, but this time the content itself contains triple backticks nested inside as part of the script being written, which breaks the extraction logic.\n\nLooking at the actual character positions, I realize the first ``` I was detecting isn't the opening fence of the outer block—it's the content of the new_text field itself. The real structure has `### MUTATION\\n` followed by ``` (opening), then the actual content with the old_text and new_text fields, then another ``` (closing). My parser was misinterpreting where the actual fence boundaries were because there are nested triple backticks in the script content that I wasn't accounting for. I see the issue now—`before_tb` captures everything before the first triple backtick, but that's only the header and opening fence, not the actual content. The `after_close` captures everything after the last one, missing the content entirely. I need to extract from after the opening fence to before the closing fence instead, which would give me the full content including `old_text` and `new_text`.","thinkingSignature":"1991738340dd5399a27c7fdc2f7f96c70c43505e33d5ef1ef7bfbf5cc59ce1d3"},{"type":"text","text":"The LLM is using triple backticks for the outer MUTATION fence now (not single backticks). My parser was designed for the single-backtick case. Let me fix to handle both cases:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_cy2v48xhh7ya_1","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\parse_mutation.py","old_string":"# Strategy:\n# 1. Find the TRIANGLE BACKTICK fences (```) - these are NESTED inside new_text\n# 2. old_text and new_text are in the SINGLE BACKTICK region before the first ```\n# 3. file: comes AFTER the last ```\n\ntb = \"```\"\ntb_positions = []\nsearch_from = 0\nwhile True:\n    p = block.find(tb, search_from)\n    if p == -1:\n        break\n    tb_positions.append(p)\n    search_from = p + 3\n\nif len(tb_positions) < 2:\n    # Fallback: whole block is the content\n    outer_content = block\n    after_close = \"\"\nelse:\n    # The triple backtick block is NESTED inside new_text\n    # Content BEFORE first ``` = contains old_text + new_text (partial)\n    # Content AFTER last ``` = contains file:\n    first_tb = tb_positions[0]\n    last_tb = tb_positions[-1]\n    before_tb = block[:first_tb]  # old_text + new_text\n    after_close = block[last_tb + 3:]  # file: + aftermath\n\n# Extract old_text: from before_tb\nold_match = re.search(r'^old_text:\\s*(.+)$', before_tb, re.MULTILINE)\nold_text = old_match.group(1).strip() if old_match else \"\"","new_string":"# Strategy:\n# Find all triple backtick (```) positions. There are two cases:\n# Case 1 (single-backtick outer): old_text/new_text before first ```, file: after last ```\n# Case 2 (triple-backtick outer): content between first and last ```, file: after last ```\n# Case 3 (no fences): whole block is content\n\ntb = \"```\"\ntb_positions = []\nsearch_from = 0\nwhile True:\n    p = block.find(tb, search_from)\n    if p == -1:\n        break\n    tb_positions.append(p)\n    search_from = p + 3\n\nif len(tb_positions) >= 2:\n    # There are nested triple backtick fences\n    # Content is between the FIRST and LAST ``` (outer block)\n    # The fences at tb_positions[0] and tb_positions[-1] are the outer wrapper\n    first_tb = tb_positions[0]\n    last_tb = tb_positions[-1]\n    outer_content = block[first_tb + 3:last_tb]  # between first and last fences\n    after_close = block[last_tb + 3:]  # after closing fence\nelif len(tb_positions) == 1:\n    # Only one fence — can't determine outer block\n    outer_content = block\n    after_close = \"\"\nelse:\n    # No fences — whole block is the content\n    outer_content = block\n    after_close = \"\"\n\n# Extract old_text: from outer_content\nold_match = re.search(r'^old_text:\\s*(.+)$', outer_content, re.MULTILINE)\nold_text = old_match.group(1).strip() if old_match else \"\""}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":94910,"output":1139,"cacheRead":13731,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":109780,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774287704153}}
