{"type":"message","id":"17203668","parentId":"82bfaa00","timestamp":"2026-03-23T17:44:12.329Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The OOM issue is at line 73: `$updated = $current -replace [regex]::Escape($oldText), $newText`. This is doing a regex replace which can consume a lot of memory for large files and large replacement strings.\n\nThe issue is that `$newText` here is the 2466-char content from the parsed mutation. If the target file is also large, the regex engine might be consuming too much memory.\n\nActually wait — the OOM happened DURING the mutation application of the NEW mutation (the one with 2466-char new_text). But the file was `research/TIC-EXPERIMENT.md` which is a new file. \n\nFor a new file, the old text check would have found the `[NEW_FILE]` marker and created the file directly without doing a replace operation, so the OOM must have occurred when applying a subsequent mutation instead.\n\nLooking at the log more carefully, the second mutation (a 2466-char new_text for file 'a') failed to apply and was rejected. The OOM happened before the log message appeared, which suggests the system ran out of memory while trying to process the mutation application rather than during the actual file operation. I'm realizing the `[NEW_FILE]` check happens after the old text search fails, so the OutOfMemoryException must be occurring during the regex replace operation itself on the current file content. The real issue is likely that the oldText contains regex metacharacters that make the escape and replace operation consume massive amounts of memory when dealing with a 2466-character newText value. The OOM likely occurred when processing the second proposed mutation with the large new_text value, which would have triggered the regex replace operation on an existing file. Since the new_text was parsed as 'a', it wouldn't match anything in the file, but the operation itself could still consume significant memory before failing. the regex `.` doesn't match newlines unless the Singleline flag is used. With `-replace`, there's no flag enabled by default, so the regex engine can't match across line breaks in the original text. This means the pattern `[NEW_FILE]` would only match if it appears on a single line, which might not happen in the actual file content. I'm realizing the `[NEW_FILE]` marker is actually the placeholder I use to indicate a new file in the mutation content itself, not something that's in the file being checked. The real problem is that when the oldText lookup fails and triggers the `[NEW_FILE]` case, that creates the file, but then the subsequent mutations still try to apply replacements to files that may not exist or may have been created incorrectly. `$newText` is only 1 character, so the replace itself should be quick. The OOM is likely coming from the regex engine struggling with `$current` containing a massive amount of text. For a single-character replacement like this, I should use simple string replacement instead of regex to avoid the overhead. I think the better approach is to switch from `-replace` to a simple `.Replace()` method for these single-character oldText values, which avoids regex overhead entirely.","thinkingSignature":"86c77cc99d5ac0d46826c828e63ae1a55cc7c2e0b345bd5171a38a6672420a0e"},{"type":"text","text":"OOM on the regex replace for the second mutation (large new_text). Fix: use simple string replace instead of regex for multiline content:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_d31oumzwyqnk_1","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\pulse.ps1","oldText":"        $current = Get-Content $fullPath -Raw\n        if ($current -notlike \"*$oldText*\") {\n            Move-Item $mfile.FullName \"$rejectedDir\\$( $mfile.Name)\" -Force\n            $rejectedMutations += \"$file (old text not found)\"\n            continue\n        }\n        $updated = $current -replace [regex]::Escape($oldText), $newText\n        $