{"type":"message","id":"e68326a2","parentId":"b7e126b7","timestamp":"2026-03-23T17:51:26.731Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The `.llm_response.txt` has some terminal escape codes (`[31;1m...`) and Unicode characters (like `\\u2192` which is `→`). The Python script is failing because it CAN read the file but the raw bytes contain ANSI escape codes which corrupt the parsing. The call_llm.py writes to the file, and the ANSI codes end up in the file.\n\nWait, no — the call_llm.py script writes the API response content directly. If the response contains ANSI codes... that means the LLM is actually outputting those codes in its response. That's weird.\n\nActually, looking at it more carefully — the `[31;1m` is an ANSI escape code for red bold text. \n\nSo the LLM is actually generating these escape sequences in its response, which shouldn't happen. Let me check what the call_llm.py script is actually doing with the output, and whether the PowerShell invocation is somehow passing stderr content back to the response file instead of just stdout. So the issue is that `call_llm.py` is writing the LLM response directly to `.llm_response.txt`, and those ANSI color codes from stderr are getting mixed into the response content itself rather than being stripped out separately.\n\nThe fix would be to either write only stdout to the response file and let stderr go to the console, or add a step to strip those ANSI codes out of the response before saving it. That way the response file contains clean output instead of corrupted content with embedded terminal codes. So the cleanest fix is to have call_llm.py strip ANSI codes from the LLM response content before writing to the file, rather than trying to separate stdout and stderr output streams. Let me update that script.","thinkingSignature":"43e36a005662b13dc3b19fe4aab662c2af873f0417ca36f33a15ae31b3664454"},{"type":"text","text":"The LLM response file has embedded ANSI escape codes (the `[31;1m` etc.) from the stderr mixing. Need to strip them in `call_llm.py`:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_0ngmrz4rgnk2_1","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\call_llm.py"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":97172,"output":427,"cacheRead":13731,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":111330,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774288273825}}
{"type":"message","id":"7432c01c","parentId":"e68326a2","timestamp":"2026-03-23T17:51:26.854Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_0ngmrz4rgnk2_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\"\"\"\nllm.py — clean LLM call wrapper for sandbox pulse\nCalls MiniMax-M2.7 API and writes response to .llm_response.txt\nPython subprocess avoids PowerShell heredoc/encoding issues.\n\"\"\"\nimport sys, os, json, urllib.request, urllib.error\n\nSCRIPT_DIR = os.path.dirname(os.path.abspath(__file__))\nRESPONSE_FILE = os.path.join(SCRIPT_DIR, \".llm_response.txt\")\n\ndef get_api_key():\n    with open(os.path.join(SCRIPT_DIR, \".llm_key\")) as f:\n        return f.read().strip()\n\ndef call_llm(prompt, model=\"MiniMax-M2.7\", max_tokens=1200):\n    api_key = get_api_key()\n    url = \"https://api.minimax.io/v1/chat/completions\"\n    payload = {\"model\": model, \"max_tokens\": max_tokens, \"messages\": [{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": prompt}]}\n    data = json.dumps(payload).encode(\"utf-8\")\n    req = urllib.request.Request(url, data=data, headers={\"Authorization\": f\"Bearer {api_key}\", \"Content-Type\": \"application/json\"}, method=\"POST\")\n    try:\n        with urllib.request.urlopen(req, timeout=60) as resp:\n            result = json.loads(resp.read().decode(\"utf-8\"))\n            choices = result.get(\"choices\", [])\n            if choices:\n                content = choices[0].get(\"message\", {}).get(\"content\", \"\")\n                return content or \"\"\n            return \"\"\n    except urllib.error.HTTPError as e:\n        return f\"HTTP_ERROR:{e.code}:{e.read().decode('utf-8', errors='replace')}\"\n    except Exception as e:\n        return f\"ERROR:{type(e).__name__}:{str(e)}\"\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    if len(sys.argv) < 2:\n        print(\"Usage: python llm.py <prompt_file>\", file=sys.stderr)\n        sys.exit(1)\n    with open(sys.argv[1], encoding=\"utf-8\") as f:\n        prompt = f.read()\n    result = call_llm(prompt)\n    # Write to file to avoid Windows console encoding issues (Greek, emoji, etc.)\n    with open(RESPONSE_FILE, \"w\", encoding=\"utf-8\") as f:\n        f.write(result)\n    # Also print to stderr for logging\n    print(f\"LLM response written to {RESPONSE_FILE}: {len(result)} chars\", file=sys.stderr)\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774288286822}}
{"type":"message","id":"b609357d","parentId":"7432c01c","timestamp":"2026-03-23T17:51:51.610Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The `call_llm.py` writes the response to `.llm_response.txt`. But somehow the file contains ANSI escape codes. This is very odd. The LLM wouldn't output ANSI codes. Unless...\n\nOh! I bet the problem is different. The PowerShell process that runs `python call_llm.py` might be capturing some ANSI escape sequences that PowerShell itself emits when displaying colored output, and those get captured as part of the output.\n\nActually, looking more carefully: the ANSI codes `[31;1m` are being written to the file. These are terminal color codes. The LLM wouldn't generate these. So somehow, the Python script is writing these to the file.\n \nNow I see the real issue — the PowerShell subprocess redirects both stdout and stderr, but `call_llm.py` writes its output to a file, not stdout. When PowerShell displays stderr content from the subprocess, it might be wrapping it with its own formatting codes that get captured as part of the output stream rather than being written directly to the terminal.\n\nBut wait, the file contains actual ANSI codes like `[31;1m`, which suggests these might be coming from the Python process itself. Python doesn't normally output color codes unless something is explicitly formatting the output that way. Let me reconsider whether the LLM response might actually contain these formatting characters as part of its text content. Looking at the stderr output, I can see the `ERROR: no MUTATION block` message is wrapped in ANSI codes, which means stderr is capturing both the Python script's error messages and the echo of the command itself from PowerShell's execution context.\n\nThe real issue is that `call_llm.py` writes its response to a file, but stderr is still being captured separately by PowerShell, and that stderr stream contains both the error messages and possibly ANSI-escaped text that shouldn't be there in the first place. the stdout is also captured but contains only the response content without ANSI codes. When PowerShell writes the captured stderr to the console, it applies its own formatting layer that wraps the text in ANSI codes, but these codes aren't actually in the raw bytes being written to the file.\n\nI'm realizing the actual file content might be clean—the ANSI codes I'm seeing are just PowerShell's console rendering, not what's stored in `.llm_response.txt`. But if the file is clean and `parse_mutation.py` can read it, then the problem must be that the \"### MUTATION\" block is genuinely missing from the response content itself. I should check whether the LLM is actually including that section or if something stripped it out. The response file should have 3227 bytes of clean UTF-8, but Python's string indexing is failing on the `\\u2192` character during the `repr()` call—this is a display encoding issue on Windows cp1252, not a file corruption problem. I need to add error handling to the parser so it can gracefully skip malformed characters instead of crashing. Looking at the actual error output, the Python traceback shows `print('Last 500:', repr(raw[-500:]))` failed with a UnicodeEncodeError, meaning the terminal can't handle the Unicode characters being printed. The \"ERROR: no MUTATION block\" message came from the parser itself, not from the printing code, so the real issue is that the LLM response in the file doesn't contain the \"### MUTATION\" marker at all—either the LLM didn't produce it or something stripped it out. Let me verify what's actually in that response file.","thinkingSignature":"e68691717b392ba2fd5e008b7d222aa168916d128eb91c3b7e8d7bb05080ad6d"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_mxgn9bzxqemn_1","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\workspace\\check_response.py","content":"import sys, os, re\nsys.stdout.reconfigure(encoding='utf-8', errors='replace')\n\nwith open(r\"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\.llm_response.txt\", \"rb\") as f:\n    raw_bytes = f.read()\n\nprint(f\"File size: {len(raw_bytes)} bytes\")\nprint(f\"Last 20 bytes hex: {raw_bytes[-20:].hex()}\")\n\n# Try to decode\ntry:\n    content = raw_bytes.decode('utf-8')\nexcept:\n    content = raw_bytes.decode('utf-8', errors='replace')\n\n# Strip ANSI codes\nansi_escape = re.compile(r'\\x1b\\[[0-9;]*[a-zA-Z]')\ncontent_clean = ansi_escape.sub('', content)\n\nprint(f\"Clean content length: {len(content_clean)}\")\nmut_idx = content_clean.find(\"### MUTATION\")\nprint(f\"MUTATION block at index: {mut_idx}\")\nif mut_idx >= 0:\n    print(f\"MUTATION block first 300: {repr(content_clean[mut_idx:mut_idx+300])}\")\nelse:\n    print(f\"Last 500 chars (clean): {repr(content_clean[-500:])}\")\n"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":97239,"output":1020,"cacheRead":13731,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":111990,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774288286866}}
