{"type":"message","id":"b8ce9b70","parentId":"d9857c0e","timestamp":"2026-03-23T17:54:28.663Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"COMPRESSION-CAUSAL-DUALITY.md was created (applied). Then the next pulse proposed SIGNIFICANCE-SCORING.md. The pulse is working correctly now.\n\nThere's still a bug: when the mutation is `[NEW_FILE]` (new file), the code tries to do `$current.Replace($oldText, $newText)` where `$oldText` is `[NEW_FILE]` and `$newText` is the content. But `[NEW_FILE]` means we're creating a new file, not replacing. So the replace should NOT be called for new file mutations.\n\nBut wait — the `[NEW_FILE]` case already handles new file creation BEFORE the Replace call. So why is Replace being called?\n \nLooking at the code structure, the `[NEW_FILE]` check runs inside the file exists block, so if the file already exists it should return early and skip the Replace. But the error suggests Replace is still being called with an empty string as the old value, which means something's not returning when it should. I think I see the issue — the `[NEW_FILE]` check is nested inside the `else` block that handles existing files, so when a file doesn't exist, it creates a new one and continues without hitting that validation. But if the file already exists and we enter the `[NEW_FILE]` branch, we should be returning early and not reaching the Replace call at all. The flow should be: file doesn't exist → creates it and returns, or file exists → `[NEW_FILE]` → moves to applied and returns. The exception message \"String cannot be of zero length\" is thrown when `Replace()` gets an empty string as the first argument, which happens because `$oldText` is empty even though the validation checks for `$oldLine` and `$fileLine` should have prevented this.\n\nLooking at the mutation format, when `old_text` is `(new file)`, it becomes `[NEW_FILE]`, so the Replace shouldn't even be called in that case. But the mutation was parsed from the old format where `old_text: (new file)` might be getting mishandled somewhere in the parsing logic. The new file was successfully created despite the error that appeared after, which suggests the Replace call with an empty string is happening on a subsequent file rather than the one that just succeeded. The error must be occurring when trying to process another mutation file in the same batch, or possibly when the script continues running after the exception is thrown. The Replace call is failing because `$oldText` is empty when the mutation gets applied as a new file. I need to add a guard to only call Replace when there's actually something to replace.","thinkingSignature":"985ca5d44171fe9fe26b0a5124b1c341fd407fe9a42e880740c21a05ccac47f2"},{"type":"text","text":"Good progress — mutations are being applied now. One remaining bug: Replace called with empty `$oldText` for new file mutations. Quick fix:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_s53p28pgeb8w_1","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\pulse.ps1","oldText":"        if ($current.Length -eq 0 -or $current -notmatch [regex]::Escape($oldText)) {","new_text":"        if ($current.Length -eq 0 -or (-not $oldText) -or $current -notmatch [regex]::Escape($oldText)) {"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":99146,"output":678,"cacheRead":13731,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":113555,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774288449249}}
