{"type":"message","id":"ae1f5aa7","parentId":"f2c879a8","timestamp":"2026-03-23T18:04:46.816Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Both files are empty. This happened because when the mutation is `[NEW_FILE]` (old_text = \"(new file)\"), the code writes `$newText` to the file, but if `$newText` is empty or the file already existed (but was empty), the mutation gets applied but the content is empty.\n\nWait, looking at the earlier output - the `research/COMPRESSION-CAUSAL-DUALITY.md` was listed as 3 bytes and empty. But earlier it was listed as 17134 bytes with other files. Let me re-check.\n\nActually wait - I see `ARCHITECTURE-COMPARISON.md 17134` which is a large file. \n\nThe directory listing got mixed up with ANSI color codes. Those 3-byte entries are genuinely empty files, likely created when `[NEW_FILE]` mutations were applied but the content never got written properly. The `old_text` being \"(new file)\" should trigger new file creation, but it seems the content assignment failed somehow. The core issue is that `[NEW_FILE]` mutations keep getting created with empty content. Looking at the pulse history, I can see the pattern—pulses are proposing these mutations, but they're all ending up as 3-byte files. The 10-pulse run hit a limit after 6 completions, which explains why some mutations show as rejected rather than applied.\n\nThe real problem is the timing: when a `[NEW_FILE]` mutation gets proposed at 13:53, the next pulse at 13:55 tries to apply it but finds the file already exists, so it marks it as already applied and never gets around to proposing a new mutation. This creates a bottleneck where the system gets stuck in a cycle of applying empty files instead of progressing to new work.\n\nLooking at the git log, there's a commit at 13:53 that created several research files including ARCHITECTURE-COMPARISON.md and others. But when I checked the research directory listing, COMPRESSION-CAUSAL-DUALITY.md showed only 3 bytes—either the file wasn't committed properly or something got corrupted during the write.\n\nActually, checking the `ls` output more carefully: those color codes are just ANSI escape sequences wrapping the numbers, so the file sizes are correct. COMPRESSION-CAUSAL-DUALITY.md really is 3 bytes, which means it got created but with empty content—likely from a `[NEW_FILE]` mutation where the newText field was blank. The system is stuck in a cycle where it's applying empty mutations to files that already exist, and the parser keeps generating empty newText. I need to fix the mutation flow so that when a file already exists, we reject the mutation instead of applying an empty one, and ensure the parser actually extracts content properly instead of proposing empty mutations.\n\nBut stepping back, the core issue is that the LLM isn't producing substantive content in the first place. Let me check what the applied mutations actually contain.","thinkingSignature":"0cc5f0ff96c16167d5c644f3ff5e40941855a3f42e2e14bf3ccaad27827c247b"},{"type":"text","text":"Files are empty — the LLM is proposing `[NEW_FILE]` with empty content. Let me check the applied mutations:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_nqvdkcmpczsd_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"Get-Content \"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\mutations\\applied\\2026-03-23 135326.mutation\" -Raw; echo \"===\"; Get-Content \"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\mutations\\applied\\2026-03-23 134224.mutation\" -Raw","timeout":5}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":95931,"output":733,"cacheRead":13731,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":110395,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774289068050}}
{"type":"message","id":"3b1b7460","parentId":"ae1f5aa7","timestamp":"2026-03-23T18:04:47.332Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_nqvdkcmpczsd_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"research/COMPRESSION-CAUSAL-DUALITY.md\n---\n[NEW_FILE]\n---\n# Compression-Causal Duality\n**Created:** 2026-03-23\n**Status:** Hypothesis Formulated\n\n## Core Insight\n\nProblem 1 (Compression) and Problem 2 (Causal Discovery) are the **same problem**.\n\n## Hypothesis\n\n> **Causal structure IS invariant structure** - A compressor that finds invariants has discovered causation.\n\n## Rationale\n\n| Compression | Causal Discovery |\n|-------------|------------------|\n| Find patterns that persist | Find mechanisms that persist |\n| Predict regular data | Predict system behavior |\n| Discard noise/variance | Isolate stable mechanisms |\n\nBoth ask: \"What stays the same across transformations?\"\n\n## Implication\n\nPhase 1 and Phase 2 collapse into one unified problem:\n- **Temporal Invariance Compression (TIC)**\n- Find what pulses share structure despite surface differences\n- That shared structure = causal mechanism\n\n## Proposed Experiment: TIC\n\n1. Collect last 20 pulse logs\n2. Compress each to invariant/variant components\n3. Measure:\n   - Classification accuracy: >70%\n   - Next-pulse prediction: >60%\n\n## References\n\n- `research/GAP-DECAY-MAPPING.md` - Gap = compression mechanism\n- `research/ARCHITECTURE-COMPARISON.md` - Three architectures, one synthesis\r\n\r\n===\r\nresearch/TIC-EXPERIMENT.md\n---\n[NEW_FILE]\n---\n**Created:** 2026-03-23\n**Status:** IN PROGRESS\n\n## Hypothesis\nCausal structure = invariant structure. A compressor that discovers invariants has discovered causation.\n\n## Method\n1. Collect last 20 pulse logs\n2. Identify repeating patterns (invariants) vs unique content (variants)\n3. Classify each segment as invariant or variant\n4. Measure: classification accuracy, compression ratio\n\n## Target Metrics\n- >70% invariant/variant classification accuracy\n- >60% next-pulse prediction accuracy\n\n## Pulse Logs to Analyze\n1. pulse_2026-03-23 134111.md (most recent)\n2. [to be populated from state/]\n\n## Progress\n- [x] Spec created\n- [ ] Collect 20 pulse logs\n- [ ] Run classification\n- [ ] Measure metrics\n- [ ] Document findings"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":485,"aggregated":"research/COMPRESSION-CAUSAL-DUALITY.md\n---\n[NEW_FILE]\n---\n# Compression-Causal Duality\n**Created:** 2026-03-23\n**Status:** Hypothesis Formulated\n\n## Core Insight\n\nProblem 1 (Compression) and Problem 2 (Causal Discovery) are the **same problem**.\n\n## Hypothesis\n\n> **Causal structure IS invariant structure** - A compressor that finds invariants has discovered causation.\n\n## Rationale\n\n| Compression | Causal Discovery |\n|-------------|------------------|\n| Find patterns that persist | Find mechanisms that persist |\n| Predict regular data | Predict system behavior |\n| Discard noise/variance | Isolate stable mechanisms |\n\nBoth ask: \"What stays the same across transformations?\"\n\n## Implication\n\nPhase 1 and Phase 2 collapse into one unified problem:\n- **Temporal Invariance Compression (TIC)**\n- Find what pulses share structure despite surface differences\n- That shared structure = causal mechanism\n\n## Proposed Experiment: TIC\n\n1. Collect last 20 pulse logs\n2. Compress each to invariant/variant components\n3. Measure:\n   - Classification accuracy: >70%\n   - Next-pulse prediction: >60%\n\n## References\n\n- `research/GAP-DECAY-MAPPING.md` - Gap = compression mechanism\n- `research/ARCHITECTURE-COMPARISON.md` - Three architectures, one synthesis\r\n\r\n===\r\nresearch/TIC-EXPERIMENT.md\n---\n[NEW_FILE]\n---\n**Created:** 2026-03-23\n**Status:** IN PROGRESS\n\n## Hypothesis\nCausal structure = invariant structure. A compressor that discovers invariants has discovered causation.\n\n## Method\n1. Collect last 20 pulse logs\n2. Identify repeating patterns (invariants) vs unique content (variants)\n3. Classify each segment as invariant or variant\n4. Measure: classification accuracy, compression ratio\n\n## Target Metrics\n- >70% invariant/variant classification accuracy\n- >60% next-pulse prediction accuracy\n\n## Pulse Logs to Analyze\n1. pulse_2026-03-23 134111.md (most recent)\n2. [to be populated from state/]\n\n## Progress\n- [x] Spec created\n- [ ] Collect 20 pulse logs\n- [ ] Run classification\n- [ ] Measure metrics\n- [ ] Document findings","cwd":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774289087318}}
{"type":"message","id":"b81e5b57","parentId":"3b1b7460","timestamp":"2026-03-23T18:05:02.988Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good - so COMPRESSION-CAUSAL-DUALITY.md (1240 chars) was applied correctly and TIC-EXPERIMENT.md (776 chars) was applied correctly. But in the research directory, they show as 3 bytes. This is very confusing.\n\nWait - maybe the `.mutation` files in `applied/` have the content and the actual `.md` files in `research/` were overwritten with empty content by a subsequent mutation.\n\nLet me look at what the current TIC-EXPERIMENT.md content is. Earlier I saw it as 3 bytes. But the mutation file has 776 bytes of content. So somehow the .md file got overwritten.\n \nOh, I think I see it now - the applied mutation files contain the full new text, and when a mutation gets applied, it should replace the entire file. But the `echo \"---\"` approach is creating 3-byte files instead of writing the actual content. That's why the .md files are ending up empty while the mutation files have the correct content stored. I see the problem now—when the first mutation creates COMPRESSION-CAUSAL-DUALITY.md with actual content, it gets moved to applied. But then when TIC-EXPERIMENT.md is proposed as a NEW_FILE and the next pulse tries to apply it, the current file check might be passing (even though the content is empty), or the Replace operation is writing empty content to the file.\n\nThe real issue is that TIC-EXPERIMENT.md keeps getting proposed repeatedly as a NEW_FILE, and each time it's applied, it overwrites with empty content. The pipeline should detect that the file already exists with content and reject the duplicate proposal, but something in the file existence or content check isn't working correctly.\n\nI need to fix the logic so that when a NEW_FILE mutation finds an existing file (regardless of content), it gets rejected immediately instead of being applied again.","thinkingSignature":"05a08d7dea457bf0b9fcc9cbfe7c6bed85652040886ed604e62f5f663d1e7fe6"},{"type":"text","text":"Found it — `[NEW_FILE]` mutations are overwriting existing files with empty content. Need to reject `[NEW_FILE]` if file already exists:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_9v5nm4qwukx9_1","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\pulse.ps1","oldText":"        # File exists — [NEW_FILE] on an existing file means it's already done\n        if ($oldText -eq \"[NEW_FILE]\") {\n            Move-Item $mfile.FullName \"$appliedDir\\$( $mfile.Name)\" -Force\n            Write-Host \"[mutation accepted] $file (already exists)\"\n            $appliedMutations += \"$file (already applied)\"\n            continue\n        }","new_string":"        # File exists — [NEW_FILE] on an existing file means reject (don't overwrite)\n        if ($oldText -eq \"[NEW_FILE]\") {\n            Move-Item $mfile.FullName \"$rejectedDir\\$( $mfile.Name)\" -Force\n            $rejectedMutations += \"$file (file already exists — rejecting to preserve content)\"\n            Write-Host \"[mutation rejected] $file (file already exists)\"\n            continue\n        }"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":96332,"output":649,"cacheRead":13731,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":110712,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774289087340}}
