{"type":"message","id":"22f8bb97","parentId":"ed842c4e","timestamp":"2026-03-23T19:30:12.804Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"So botshoppebot WAS replying once (recognized Zach), but now it's not replying at all. The issue is likely that it's using the same Telegram bot token and webhook as the main Nova bot, or something similar.\n\nLet me think about this. The \"botshoppebot\" — could this be a bot that was set up as the Telegram bot for the OpenClaw instance, separate from the main account? Or is this a completely different bot?\n\nIf botshoppebot told Zach \"you're not Zach\" — that's the authorization check working. But then it stopped replying entirely. \n\nPossible issues:\n1. The webhook for botshoppebot is conflicting with the main Nova bot's webhook — if both use the same Telegram bot token, only one can have the webhook set.\n\n\n2. The botshoppebot webhook might be routing to Nova instead, so messages never reach botshoppebot's handler.\n3. The botshoppebot might be experiencing webhook issues similar to what we've seen before.\n\nI need to find the botshoppebot token — it's probably in TOOLS.md or the OpenClaw config. Though I'm realizing botshoppebot might be registered under a different OpenClaw instance entirely, which would explain why it's not responding to the same authorized user list.\n\nLooking at TOOLS.md, there's a Telegram webhook already pointing to Nova's bot token (8587631426:AAHvqmo--g25LqsClCWCXj4m617cn2v7V7Q). If botshoppebot is using a different bot token with its own webhook, that could be the conflict — both can't use webhooks simultaneously on the same account. The issue is likely that botshoppebot's webhook is either pointing to the wrong endpoint or not set up at all, so messages aren't reaching it. webhook URL is invalid. If the cloudflared tunnel changed, the webhook would still point to the old URL and wouldn't receive messages.\n\nBut actually — the current Nova bot IS working (I'm receiving messages through it). So the webhook for Nova's bot token is working.\n\nThe question is: does botshoppebot have its own bot token, or is it using the same one?\n\nIf botshoppebot is a SEPARATE bot with its OWN bot token, then it needs its OWN webhook. Two bots can coexist — each has their own webhook.\n\nLet me ask Zach for the botshoppebot token so I can check its webhook status.\n\nActually, thinking about this more: \"botshoppebot\" — this might be the bot that was created when setting up the Telegram integration. The bot username is likely `@botshoppebot`. If Zach created this bot and set it up with OpenClaw, it might be using the same webhook URL as Nova but with a different bot token. The fact that it replied once saying \"you're not Zach\" suggests the bot IS receiving messages and doing an auth check — so the webhook is working — but something changed after that. If it just stopped responding, maybe the webhook URL changed when cloudflared restarted, or perhaps the bot's message handling got broken by something.","thinkingSignature":"34ef3b64956eef719683da4575000cb927c0fae867370571a1f0f72ecc011864"},{"type":"text","text":"Likely the webhook got stale. When cloudflared restarts, the tunnel URL changes and the old webhook URL stops delivering messages. Let me check:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_kvdxo7ii4c6h_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"Invoke-RestMethod \"https://api.telegram.org/bot8587631426:AAHvqmo--g25LqsClCWCXj4m617cn2v7V7Q/getWebhookInfo\" 2>$null | ConvertTo-Json -Depth 3","timeout":10}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":0,"output":765,"cacheRead":117923,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":118688,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774294192862}}
