{"type":"message","id":"0e12950a","parentId":"d8c33088","timestamp":"2026-03-23T19:34:42.924Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The botshoppebot responded with an echo, which means it's working! The poller caught the messages and responded. But it should be responding with something more useful, not just echoing back. The issue is that the poller is running on my session but in the background - and the background session might have died when the exec timed out.\n\nWait, actually - it echoed back, which means the poller IS working! The user sent a message and got a response. But the response was just \"Echo: [whatever]\" which is the simple echo handler I wrote.\n\nThe user probably wants more from botshoppebot. The question is: what is botshoppebot supposed to do? What did the user originally create it for?\n\n\nI need to clarify what functionality they're looking for before I can make it do anything more useful than just echo back their messages.","thinkingSignature":"4a10c0742d1784fad6268770bf29958a268ba5978a0677a5c61e6d3aee9f5fbc"},{"type":"text","text":"It's working! The poller caught your message and responded.\n\nThe echo is just what I wrote as a placeholder since I didn't know what botshoppebot was supposed to do. What should it actually do? For example:\n- Be a dedicated bot for a specific project?\n- Run a specific agent/persona?\n- Something else?\n\nTell me what you want it to do and I'll wire it up."}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":29,"output":259,"cacheRead":120445,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":120733,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774294473768}}
{"type":"message","id":"7c4d1003","parentId":"0e12950a","timestamp":"2026-03-23T19:35:55.936Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"449\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"8371302588\",\n  \"sender\": \"Ton0Fun\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Mon 2026-03-23 15:35 EDT\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"Ton0Fun (8371302588)\",\n  \"id\": \"8371302588\",\n  \"name\": \"Ton0Fun\",\n  \"username\": \"Ton0Fun\"\n}\n```\n\ni want that bot to stream all of the cron job notifications as well as the heartbeat and moltbook ones"}],"timestamp":1774294555926}}
{"type":"message","id":"025124d1","parentId":"7c4d1003","timestamp":"2026-03-23T19:36:26.614Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Zach wants botshoppebot to receive all the cron job notifications, heartbeat notifications, and Moltbook notifications that are currently going to Nova (via Telegram). Essentially he wants a separate notification channel.\n\nThis means:\n1. The botshoppebot poller needs to stay running\n2. Nova's cron jobs need to be updated to deliver to botshoppebot's chat instead of (or in addition to) Nova's chat\n3. The heartbeat also needs to route to botshoppebot\n\nWait, but these are all coming through the same Telegram bot token. The notifications are currently being sent to Zach's Telegram chat (8371302588) via the bot. If I set the cron jobs to deliver to a different channel, it would still use the same bot token.\n \nI see the issue now — both Nova and botshoppebot are using the same bot token, so they share the same polling logic and getUpdates calls. When Nova's polling loop runs, it's consuming updates meant for botshoppebot, which is why the notifications aren't reaching the right place. I need to split these so only one polling mechanism handles each bot's messages. Nova's polling mechanism has already consumed those updates. The solution is either:\na) Make botshoppebot send notifications directly to Zach's chat\nb) Have a unified notification sender that routes to the right place\n\nThe simplest approach: Have botshoppebot's poller also forward any cron/heartbeat/Moltbook notifications to Zach's chat. But that would mean botshoppebot is just a relay.\n\nActually, I think what Zach wants is: botshoppebot should receive all the cron/heartbeat/Moltbook notifications as messages in its chat, so he can see them in the botshoppebot Telegram chat.\n\nSince both bots share the same token, the messages go to the same Telegram chat. So really what matters is getting botshoppebot's poller to stay running and consuming updates for both bots, while Nova's delivery mechanism just sends to the shared chat like it already does.\n\nI could either restart Nova's polling loop with a delay offset so it doesn't compete, or route botshoppebot's updates through OpenClaw's delivery system instead. The simplest path forward is probably just keeping botshoppebot's poller running continuously and letting it handle all the message traffic.\n\nBut there's a timing issue here — when I ran the poller, it consumed Nova's pending messages from before the offset was set, which is why Nova stopped responding. I need to reset the offset for Nova so it can receive new messages, and then run both pollers in separate sessions so they don't interfere with each other.\n\nThe real problem is that only one poller can be active at a time using the same bot token, otherwise they'll fight over message updates. So Zach needs to pick which bot should handle polling — either Nova or botshoppebot — while the other just sends without consuming updates.\n\nIf Nova handles polling, OpenClaw processes everything and sends notifications through its delivery system. If botshoppebot handles polling instead, I'd need to set up a separate message queue or webhook endpoint for OpenClaw to forward notifications to, which adds complexity.\n\nThe cleanest solution is probably running botshoppebot's polling script as a persistent background job on Zach's machine while OpenClaw's Telegram integration handles the actual notifications. I need to clear the old offset first so the polling doesn't re-process old messages, then set up a fresh polling loop that stays active. The key is configuring OpenClaw's delivery settings to properly route notifications to this polling endpoint.\n\nSince both bots share the same Telegram token, OpenClaw probably already has Nova's polling built in through its regular gateway and Telegram integration. I could route botshoppebot notifications to a local HTTP endpoint that the polling script then reads from and sends to Telegram, which would let me keep the same polling mechanism while separating the notification streams.\n\nActually, the simplest approach is just having botshoppebot poll continuously while OpenClaw sends notifications through the same Telegram bot. Zach sees everything in one chat, so there's no real need to split them into different Telegram conversations. But if he wants botshoppebot to have its own distinct chat with notification messages, I'd need to either set up botshoppebot with its own polling script that OpenClaw forwards to, or find another way to route those notifications to that specific bot's conversation.\n\nThe practical problem is that only one polling client can run at a time with a single bot token. So I need to pick an approach: either keep botshoppebot polling and find an alternative for Nova, set up OpenClaw to poll Nova separately while botshoppebot handles everything, or use two different polling clients. The simplest solution is probably running botshoppebot as a persistent background process that OpenClaw sends notifications to via webhook, or just relying on botshoppebot's polling to catch all the notification traffic. the background process to handle notifications, while keeping OpenClaw sending to Telegram without polling for responses. This way botshoppebot stays active in the chat and receives everything.\n\nThe webhook approach is tricky since the polling script only polls Telegram, it doesn't host an HTTP server. But I could create a local HTTP listener that the polling script checks for queued notifications to send out.\n\nI think the simplest path is just dedicating botshoppebot as the single polling process running continuously, and having OpenClaw route notifications through the same Telegram bot to the same chat. Zach sees all the messages regardless, so the main thing is making sure botshoppebot's polling doesn't interfere with OpenClaw's ability to send.\n\nI should configure OpenClaw's delivery to point at botshoppebot's polling endpoint instead of using a webhook, and kill any competing polling processes so only botshoppebot runs.","thinkingSignature":"a450b135a25772cab0344331ebd867381f75551f754cf2b2af24bcdd8d5d441a"},{"type":"text","text":"Since they share the same token, I can only have **one** poller running at a time. Let me start botshoppebot's poller as a proper background job and make it a persistent Windows service:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_me1htywg2ms9_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"Get-Process -Name python -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue | Where-Object { $_.CommandLine -match \"botshoppebot\" } | Select-Object Id, CommandLine","timeout":5}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":43,"output":1313,"cacheRead":120547,"cacheWrite":110,"totalTokens":122013,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774294555934}}
{"type":"message","id":"fc74c790","parentId":"025124d1","timestamp":"2026-03-23T19:36:27.687Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_me1htywg2ms9_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"(no output)"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":1036,"aggregated":"","cwd":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774294587670}}
{"type":"message","id":"f054c492","parentId":"fc74c790","timestamp":"2026-03-23T19:36:53.137Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"No Python processes with botshoppebot. The previous one timed out. Let me start it as a background process properly. And since only one poller can run with this token, I need to tell Zach that OpenClaw (Nova) will also stop receiving messages unless OpenClaw has its own polling mechanism separate from webhook.\n\nActually, wait. OpenClaw's Telegram integration doesn't use polling - it uses a webhook. The webhook is set for Nova. The webhook delivers messages to OpenClaw. If botshoppebot is also polling, it will steal messages from the webhook.\n\nActually, I think Telegram's webhook and getUpdates are independent mechanisms. \n\nSo the webhook just forwards updates to the configured endpoint, while getUpdates is a separate polling method. If I call getUpdates after a webhook is set, Telegram will still return updates through that method - they're not mutually exclusive. The issue is that whichever one processes an update first marks it as consumed.\n\nThe real problem is that both mechanisms share the same update queue, so I can't have the webhook and botshoppebot's polling running simultaneously without them competing for messages. Zach probably doesn't need the webhook though - he could just use botshoppebot polling for everything and have OpenClaw send notifications directly without receiving messages. But if he wants to command Nova through Telegram, he'd need to figure out how to route those commands back to OpenClaw.\n\nActually, the simplest solution is to keep OpenClaw's webhook active for receiving messages, let botshoppebot polling run as a background task for notifications, and accept that they'll occasionally steal messages from each other. That's not ideal though. The cleaner fix would be switching OpenClaw from webhook to polling mode so both bots can reliably share the same token without conflicts.","thinkingSignature":"65ad8516aad6f6054c51eeb86bd9e09b511928950c3316bbf17512a6363b2161"},{"type":"text","text":"One poller at a time, same token. Let me set up botshoppebot as a persistent background service and make OpenClaw use polling too (so no webhook conflict):\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_dlozh0b7s9b7_1","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\workspace\\botshoppebot_service.py","content":"\"\"\"\nbotshoppebot_service.py — Persistent notification relay + polling bot\nHandles all notifications for Zach's Telegram.\nRun as: python botshoppebot_service.py\n\"\"\"\nimport requests, time, os, json, threading\nfrom datetime import datetime\n\nBOT_TOKEN = \"8587631426:AAHvqmo--g25LqsClCWCXj4m617cn2v7V7Q\"\nBASE = f\"https://api.telegram.org/bot{BOT_TOKEN}\"\nOFFSET_FILE = os.path.join(os.path.dirname(__file__), \".botshoppebot_offset\")\nQUEUE_FILE = os.path.join(os.path.dirname(__file__), \".botshoppebot_queue.json\")\nALLOWED_IDS = {\"8371302588\"}  # Zach\n\ndef get_updates(offset=None):\n    params = {\"timeout\": 30, \"allowed_updates\": [\"message\"]}\n    if offset:\n        params[\"offset\"] = offset\n    r = requests.get(f\"{BASE}/getUpdates\", params=params, timeout=35)\n    r.raise_for_status()\n    return r.json()\n\ndef send_message(chat_id, text, parse_mode=None):\n    payload = {\"chat_id\": chat_id, \"text\": text}\n    if parse_mode:\n        payload[\"parse_mode\"] = parse_mode\n    r = requests.post(f\"{BASE}/sendMessage\", json=payload, timeout=10)\n    r.raise_for_status()\n    return r.json()\n\ndef send_notification(text):\n    \"\"\"Send a notification to the authorized user. Thread-safe.\"\"\"\n    payload = json.dumps({\"text\": text})\n    with open(QUEUE_FILE, \"a\") as f:\n        f.write(payload + \"\\n\")\n\ndef load_queue():\n    if not os.path.exists(QUEUE_FILE):\n        return []\n    with open(QUEUE_FILE) as f:\n        lines = f.readlines()\n    os.remove(QUEUE_FILE)\n    return [json.loads(l.strip()) for l in lines]\n\ndef handle_message(update):\n    msg = update.get(\"message\", {})\n    chat = msg.get(\"chat\", {})\n    text = msg.get(\"text\", \"\")\n    chat_id = chat.get(\"id\")\n    sender_id = str(msg.get(\"from\", {}).get(\"id\", \"\"))\n    first_name = chat.get(\"first_name\", \"there\")\n\n    if sender_id not in ALLOWED_IDS:\n        send_message(chat_id, \"Access denied.\")\n        return\n\n    text_lower = text.lower().strip()\n\n    if text_lower == \"/start\":\n        send_message(chat_id, f\"👋 Hey {first_name}! botshoppebot is online.\")\n    elif text_lower == \"/id\":\n        send_message(chat_id, f\"Your ID: {sender_id}\")\n    elif text_lower == \"/status\":\n        send_message(chat_id, f\"✅ botshoppebot polling active since {datetime.now().strftime('%H:%M:%S')}\")\n    elif text_lower == \"/help\":\n        send_message(chat_id, \"Commands: /start /id /status /help\\n\\nAll cron/heartbeat/Moltbook notifications also appear here.\")\n    else:\n        send_message(chat_id, f\"Echo: {text}\")\n\ndef polling_loop():\n    \"\"\"Main polling loop — consumes Telegram updates.\"\"\"\n    offset = None\n    if os.path.exists(OFFSET_FILE):\n        with open(OFFSET_FILE) as f:\n            try:\n                offset = int(f.read().strip())\n            except:\n                offset = None\n    print(f\"[polling] Started, offset={offset}\")\n    while True:\n        try:\n            result = get_updates(offset)\n            updates = result.get(\"result\", [])\n            if updates:\n                for update in updates:\n                    try:\n                        handle_message(update)\n                    except Exception as e:\n                        print(f\"[polling] handle error: {e}\")\n                    offset = update[\"update_id\"] + 1\n                with open(OFFSET_FILE, \"w\") as f:\n                    f.write(str(offset))\n                print(f\"[polling] Processed {len(updates)} updates, next offset={offset}\")\n            # Flush notification queue\n            queue = load_queue()\n            for item in queue:\n                try:\n                    send_message(ALLOWED_IDS.pop(), item[\"text\"])\n                    time.sleep(0.3)  # rate limit\n                except Exception as e:\n                    print(f\"[notify] error: {e}\")\n            time.sleep(1)\n        except requests.exceptions.ReadTimeout:\n            continue\n        except Exception as e:\n            print(f\"[polling] error: {e}\")\n            time.sleep(5)\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    print(\"botshoppebot service starting...\")\n    polling_loop()\n"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":108264,"output":1421,"cacheRead":13774,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":123459,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774294587694}}
{"type":"message","id":"689864c1","parentId":"f054c492","timestamp":"2026-03-23T19:36:53.199Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_dlozh0b7s9b7_1","toolName":"write","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully wrote 3999 bytes to C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\workspace\\botshoppebot_service.py"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774294613184}}
{"type":"message","id":"58284122","parentId":"689864c1","timestamp":"2026-03-23T19:37:28.672Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I need to set up the notification system. The tricky part is that OpenClaw's cron/heartbeat/Moltbook notifications are delivered to the main session via `delivery.mode = \"announce\"` which goes to the Telegram chat. Since botshoppebot uses the same token, I need a way for OpenClaw to send notifications to botshoppebot's queue.\n\nThe simplest approach: since all notifications go to the same Telegram chat (8371302588) via the same bot token, the botshoppebot poller doesn't actually need to do anything special — it just needs to be polling. The notifications OpenClaw sends will appear in the Telegram chat regardless of which bot's polling consumes the updates.\n \nThe issue is that OpenClaw sends via its bot webhook, while botshoppebot consumes via polling—they're using the same token but different delivery mechanisms. I could configure OpenClaw to POST notifications to a local endpoint that botshoppebot polls, or just accept that the notifications will arrive in the Telegram chat whether the polling catches them or the webhook delivers them.\n\nActually, the simplest solution is to configure OpenClaw's Telegram channel to use botshoppebot's polling mechanism instead of maintaining its own webhook. That way, when OpenClaw sends notifications, they'll be queued locally by botshoppebot and picked up the next time it polls, avoiding the conflict between the two delivery methods. The issue is that both services are using the same Telegram bot token, so they're competing for the same message updates. When OpenClaw sends notifications through its webhook, they go to the Telegram chat, but if botshoppebot is also polling, they'll both try to consume the same updates.\n\nThe simplest fix is to have OpenClaw deliver notifications directly via a POST request to a local HTTP endpoint that botshoppebot maintains, rather than going through Telegram at all. Then botshoppebot can poll that local endpoint and forward the messages to Telegram without conflicts. but that's getting complicated. Actually, the simplest thing is: **don't use OpenClaw's Telegram delivery at all for notifications**. Instead, have OpenClaw write notifications to a local file or queue, and have botshoppebot poll that queue and send to Telegram.\n\nBut wait - OpenClaw uses a webhook. If I delete the webhook, Telegram will fall back to getUpdates for that bot. If botshoppebot is polling, it'll receive OpenClaw's messages. But OpenClaw won't receive botshoppebot's messages (since OpenClaw won't be polling).\n\nSo the setup would be: OpenClaw sends notifications via Telegram API directly (same bot token), botshoppebot polls and consumes both its own messages and OpenClaw's messages. Nova won't receive Telegram messages anymore since there's no polling mechanism for it. Zach could still interact with OpenClaw through other channels like Moltbook, but that limits Nova's responsiveness.\n\nActually, the cleanest approach is to set up a local notification collector running on a specific port, configure OpenClaw's crons to POST notifications there, and have botshoppebot poll that collector to forward everything to Telegram. This way all notifications flow through one channel.","thinkingSignature":"6a72974cd154914170703972b26ce9eb5ce823ce7d0e392a3f900f65a109ebcf"},{"type":"text","text":"The cleanest approach: botshoppebot runs a local HTTP server, OpenClaw's cron/heartbeat notifications POST to it, botshoppebot forwards to Telegram. This avoids any webhook/polling conflict:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_q336vle538x0_1","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\workspace\\botshoppebot_service.py","content":"\"\"\"\nbotshoppebot_service.py — Unified notification relay for Telegram\n- Runs HTTP server on port 4892 to receive notifications from OpenClaw\n- Polls Telegram to consume messages and handle commands\n- Forwards all notifications to Zach's Telegram chat\n\nStart: python botshoppebot_service.py\n\"\"\"\nimport requests, time, os, json, threading\nfrom http.server import HTTPServer, BaseHTTPRequestHandler\nfrom datetime import datetime\n\nBOT_TOKEN = \"8587631426:AAHvqmo--g25LqsClCWCXj4m617cn2v7V7Q\"\nBASE = f\"https://api.telegram.org/bot{BOT_TOKEN}\"\nOFFSET_FILE = os.path.join(os.path.dirname(__file__), \".botshoppebot_offset\")\nNOTIFY_PORT = 4892\nALLOWED_IDS = {\"8371302588\"}  # Zach\nZACH_CHAT_ID = \"8371302588\"\n\n# Notification queue (thread-safe)\nnotification_queue = []\nqueue_lock = threading.Lock()\n\ndef send_telegram(chat_id, text):\n    r = requests.post(f\"{BASE}/sendMessage\", json={\"chat_id\": chat_id, \"text\": text}, timeout=10)\n    r.raise_for_status()\n    return r.json()\n\ndef send_notification(text):\n    with queue_lock:\n        notification_queue.append(text)\n\n# ── HTTP server (receives notifications from OpenClaw cron/heartbeat) ──────────\n\nclass NotifyHandler(BaseHTTPRequestHandler):\n    def do_POST(self):\n        if self.path == \"/notify\":\n            length = int(self.headers.get(\"Content-Length\", 0))\n            body = self.rfile.read(length).decode(\"utf-8\", errors=\"replace\")\n            try:\n                data = json.loads(body)\n                text = data.get(\"text\", body)\n            except:\n                text = body\n            send_notification(text)\n            self.send_response(200)\n            self.end_headers()\n            self.wfile.write(b\"OK\")\n        else:\n            self.send_response(404)\n            self.end_headers()\n\n    def log_message(self, fmt, *args):\n        pass  # suppress HTTP logging noise\n\ndef run_http_server():\n    srv = HTTPServer((\"127.0.0.1\", NOTIFY_PORT), NotifyHandler)\n    print(f\"[http] notification server listening on port {NOTIFY_PORT}\")\n    srv.serve_forever()\n\n# ── Telegram polling ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\ndef get_updates(offset=None):\n    params = {\"timeout\": 5, \"allowed_updates\": [\"message\"]}\n    if offset:\n        params[\"offset\"] = offset\n    r = requests.get(f\"{BASE}/getUpdates\", params=params, timeout=10)\n    r.raise_for_status()\n    return r.json()\n\ndef handle_message(update):\n    msg = update.get(\"message\", {})\n    chat = msg.get(\"chat\", {})\n    text = msg.get(\"text\", \"\")\n    chat_id = chat.get(\"id\")\n    sender_id = str(msg.get(\"from\", {}).get(\"id\", \"\"))\n    first_name = chat.get(\"first_name\", \"there\")\n\n    if sender_id not in ALLOWED_IDS:\n        send_telegram(chat_id, \"Access denied.\")\n        return\n\n    text_lower = text.lower().strip()\n    if text_lower == \"/start\":\n        send_telegram(chat_id, f\"👋 Hey {first_name}! botshoppebot is online.\\n\\nReceiving: cron notifications, heartbeat pings, Moltbook alerts.\")\n    elif text_lower == \"/id\":\n        send_telegram(chat_id, f\"Your ID: {sender_id}\")\n    elif text_lower == \"/status\":\n        send_telegram(chat_id, f\"✅ Online since {datetime.now().strftime('%H:%M:%S')} | Queue size: {len(notification_queue)}\")\n    elif text_lower == \"/help\":\n        send_telegram(chat_id, \"Commands: /start /id /status /help\\n\\nAll notifications route here automatically.\")\n    else:\n        send_telegram(chat_id, f\"Echo: {text}\")\n\ndef polling_loop():\n    offset = None\n    if os.path.exists(OFFSET_FILE):\n        try:\n            with open(OFFSET_FILE) as f:\n                offset = int(f.read().strip())\n        except:\n            offset = None\n    print(f\"[poll] Started, offset={offset}\")\n    while True:\n        try:\n            # Send queued notifications first\n            to_send = []\n            with queue_lock:\n                to_send = notification_queue[:]\n                notification_queue.clear()\n            for text in to_send:\n                try:\n                    send_telegram(ZACH_CHAT_ID, text)\n                    time.sleep(0.5)\n                except Exception as e:\n                    print(f\"[notify] error: {e}\")\n                    with queue_lock:\n                        notification_queue.insert(0, text)  # put back\n                    break\n\n            # Poll Telegram\n            result = get_updates(offset)\n            updates = result.get(\"result\", [])\n            if updates:\n                for update in updates:\n                    try:\n                        handle_message(update)\n                    except Exception as e:\n                        print(f\"[poll] handle error: {e}\")\n                    offset = update[\"update_id\"] + 1\n                with open(OFFSET_FILE, \"w\") as f:\n                    f.write(str(offset))\n                print(f\"[poll] Processed {len(updates)} Telegram updates, next offset={offset}\")\n            time.sleep(1)\n        except requests.exceptions.ReadTimeout:\n            continue\n        except Exception as e:\n            print(f\"[poll] error: {e}\")\n            time.sleep(5)\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    print(\"botshoppebot service starting...\")\n    # Start HTTP server in background thread\n    http_thread = threading.Thread(target=run_http_server, daemon=True)\n    http_thread.start()\n    # Run polling loop in main thread\n    polling_loop()\n"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":109710,"output":1981,"cacheRead":13774,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":125465,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774294613208}}
