{"type":"message","id":"0c9e8a04","parentId":"e794b3a3","timestamp":"2026-03-23T19:46:36.059Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good, the processes are killed. Now let me restart botshoppebot properly. But I also need to fix the OpenClaw integration. The user wants:\n1. botshoppebot to receive cron/heartbeat/Moltbook notifications via polling\n2. Nova to NOT send to that bot (same token conflict)\n\nThe cleanest architecture:\n- botshoppebot polls Telegram using the shared token\n- OpenClaw's Nova sends cron/heartbeat notifications to `localhost:4892/notify` instead of via Telegram\n\nBut OpenClaw's cron delivery system sends to configured channels/recipients, not a local HTTP server. So I need to keep the OpenClaw notifications going to Nova's Telegram channel (already working), AND have botshoppebot poll for it own messages.\n \nNow I see the real constraint - with one token, only one poller can work at a time, and botshoppebot needs to handle both sending notifications and polling for incoming messages. Since OpenClaw is already using Nova's Telegram channel for delivery, I can have botshoppebot run as the poller on the shared token while OpenClaw continues routing notifications through its existing Telegram setup.","thinkingSignature":"ee6509d79612e9c6b65e268536b3c92afa168c65d6363f4205f2f6d6453eb161"},{"type":"text","text":"Port is clear. Now restart botshoppebot:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_n7iqtdat8rw0_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"Start-Process -FilePath python -ArgumentList \"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\workspace\\botshoppebot_simple.py\" -WorkingDirectory \"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\workspace\" -PassThru | Select-Object Id, HasExited; Start-Sleep -Seconds 3; curl -s -X POST \"http://127.0.0.1:4892/notify\" -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" -d \"{\\\"text\\\":\\\"✅ botshoppebot is running! Port 4892 relay active.\\\"}\"","timeout":15}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-por